info.title: UPS TrackService API
info.description:
The Track API helps retrieves current status of shipments such as Small Package 1Z, Infonotice, Mail Innovations, FGV, or UPS Freight shipments using the package number or the reference number. The tracking response data typically includes package movements/activities, destination UPS access point information, expected delivery dates/times, etc. Required parameters are the inquiryNumber, transaction ID, and transaction source.
The response returns an array of shipment objects containing detailed tracking information and status for the package(s) associated with the inquiryNumber, including current status, activity history, delivery details, package details, and more. For more information on the Track API, please visit the Product Overview page. **Note:** Data is rolled off after the 120 day retention period and may not be returned in the response after the retention period. Key Business Values: - **Near real-time tracking information**: Get up-to-date information on the status and location of your shipments, so you can keep your customers informed. - **Proof of Delivery**: Automated proof of delivery updates with signature verification to help prevent fraud and theft. - **Improved cash flow**: Reduce the time it takes to collect payments by tracking shipments and invoices electronically. # Reference - Business Rules - Appendix - Errors

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

flattened_text: The UPS Track API provides real-time tracking information for shipments like Small Package 1Z, Infonotice, Mail Innovations, FGV, or UPS Freight. You can track packages using the package number or reference number. The API response includes package movements, delivery dates, and more. Key benefits include real-time tracking, proof of delivery, and improved cash flow. Data is retained for 120 days. Explore the API documentation and sample applications on GitHub.
This OpenAPI specification defines two server URLs: one for the Customer Integration Environment at "https://wwwcie.ups.com/api" and one for Production at "https://onlinetools.ups.com/api".

parameters.name: inquiryNumber
parameters.description: The tracking number for which tracking information is requested. Each inquiry number must be between 7 and 34 characters in length.

parameters.name: locale
parameters.description: Language and country code of the user, separated by an underscore. Default value is 'en_US'

parameters.name: returnSignature
parameters.description: Indicator requesting that the delivery signature image be included as part of the response (by default the image will not be returned). Returns image bytecodes of the signature.

parameters.name: returnMilestones
parameters.description: returnMilestones

parameters.name: returnPOD
parameters.description: Return Proof of Delivery

parameters.name: transId
parameters.description: An identifier unique to the request.

parameters.name: transactionSrc
parameters.description: Identifies the client/source application that is calling

flattened_text: This endpoint allows users to retrieve tracking information for a specific package by providing a tracking number. Users can also specify additional parameters such as language, signature image inclusion, milestones, and proof of delivery. The response includes details about the package's status. The endpoint requires authentication using OAuth2.

parameters.name: referenceNumber
parameters.description: The reference number for which tracking information is requested.

parameters.name: locale
parameters.description: Language and country code of the user, separated by an underscore. Default value is 'en_US'

parameters.name: fromPickUpDate
parameters.description: The tracking information for the above reference number will be searched from this date

parameters.name: toPickUpDate
parameters.description: The tracking information for the above reference number will be searched till this date

parameters.name: refNumType
parameters.description: The Reference number type which will define the tracking information is related to small package or fgv

parameters.name: transId
parameters.description: An identifier unique to the request.

parameters.name: transactionSrc
parameters.description: Identifies the client/source application that is calling

flattened_text: This API endpoint allows users to track a package using a reference number. Users can specify the reference number, language, date range, reference number type, and request identifier. The response includes tracking information if found, with different responses for various scenarios like invalid requests or server errors. The endpoint requires OAuth2 security and falls under the "Tracking" category.

OAuth2.description:
Find your Client ID and Secret on your app info page.
1. Select \"Try It\"
2. In the Security section enter your Client ID and Secret.
3. Select \"Request Token\"
4. Enter any additional information in the Body and Parameters sections.
5. Select \"Send\" to execute your API request

flattened_text:
To use OAuth2 for authentication, follow these steps:

1. Find your Client ID and Secret on your app info page.
2. Select "Try It" and enter your Client ID and Secret in the Security section.
3. Click "Request Token."
4. Add any extra information in the Body and Parameters sections.
5. Click "Send" to run your API request.

OAuth2 uses client credentials and the token URL is https://wwwcie.ups.com/security/v1/oauth/token. The authentication method is client_secret_basic.

AccessPointInformation.title: AccessPointInformation
AccessPointInformation.description: The container that has all the information related to the access point where the package is destined for/delivered to.

flattened_text: The AccessPointInformation object contains details about the access point where a package is being sent or delivered. It includes a property for the pickup date.

Activity.title: Activity
Activity.description: Container with all activities associated with the package. Activities are returned in chronological order, with the most recent activity first.

date.description: The date of the activity. Format: YYYYMMDD

time.description: The time of the activity. Format: HHMMSS (24 hr)

flattened_text: The "Activity" object contains information about activities related to a package. Activities are listed in order from the most recent to the oldest. Each activity includes the date, time, GMT date, GMT offset, GMT time, location, and status. The date is in the format YYYYMMDD, and the time is in 24-hour format (HHMMSS).

Address.title: Address
Address.description: The container which has the physical address.

stateProvince.description: The physical address state or province.

flattened_text: This data structure represents a physical address with detailed information such as address lines, city, country, postal code, and state/province. Each address line and field has a specific purpose, like street address, city, and country. The example values provide a clear idea of how to format the address information.

AlternateTrackingNumber.title: AlternateTrackingNumber
AlternateTrackingNumber.description: The list of alternate tracking numbers associated with the package.

type.description: The type of alternate number. Non-typed numbers are typically UPS tracking numbers.

flattened_text: This object represents alternate tracking numbers for a package. It includes the alternate tracking number and its type. The number is a string, and the type specifies the kind of alternate number, such as USPS_PIC for USPS tracking numbers.

DeliveryDate.title: DeliveryDate
DeliveryDate.description: The list of delivery dates associated with the package.

date.description: The date of this delivery detail. Format - YYYYMMDD

type.description: The list of delivery dates associated with the package. Valid values: SDD - Scheduled Delivery Date RDD - Rescheduled Delivery Date DEL - Delivered Date

flattened_text: This object represents delivery dates for a package. It includes the date of the delivery detail in YYYYMMDD format and the type of delivery date (SDD for Scheduled Delivery Date, RDD for Rescheduled Delivery Date, DEL for Delivered Date).

DeliveryInformation.title: DeliveryInformation
DeliveryInformation.description: Container with all information related to the delivery of the package. Populated only when the package is delivered.

location.description: The location where the package was dropped off. For example: 'Front Door'

receivedBy.description: The individual who took possession of the package at delivery.

pod.title: POD
pod.description: Container which contains Proof of Delivery.

content.description: The base64 encoded string representation of the Delivery Proof. Note: This is considered sensitive data and may only be returned for a user that has rights to the package.

flattened_text: The `DeliveryInformation` object contains details about package delivery. It includes a delivery photo, drop-off location, Proof of Delivery (POD) with encoded delivery proof, recipient's name, and signature. This information is populated only after the package is delivered.

DeliveryPhoto.title: DeliveryPhoto
DeliveryPhoto.description: Container with all information related to the delivery photo of the package.

isNonPostalCodeCountry.description: The indication if the country does not use postal code. Valid values: 'true' this country does not use postal code. 'false' this country uses postal code

photoCaptureInd.description: The photo capture indicator. Valid values: 'Y' the photo is an photo capture. 'N' the photo is not a capture

photoDispositionCode.description: The photo disposition code. Valid values: 'V' the photo is viewable. 'N' the photo is not viewable. 'U' the photo is not stored

flattened_text: The `DeliveryPhoto` object contains information about a delivery photo for a package. It includes properties such as `isNonPostalCodeCountry` to indicate if the country uses postal codes, `photo` for the actual photo, `photoCaptureInd` to indicate if the photo is a capture, and `photoDispositionCode` to show if the photo is viewable or stored.

DeliveryTime.title: DeliveryTime
DeliveryTime.description: The container which has all delivery times associated with the package.

endTime.description: The end time of a window or the committed time or the delivered time. Only returned when the type is “EDW” or “CDW” or “IDW” or “CMT” or “DEL”. Format: HHMMSS (24 hr)

startTime.description: The start time of a delivery. Only returned when the type is “EDW” or “CDW” or “IDW”. Format: HHMMSS (24 hr).

type.description:
The date of this delivery detail.
Valid values:

EOD - End of Day
CMT - Commit Time
EDW - Estimated Delivery Window **
CDW - Confirmed Delivery Window **
IDW - Imminent Delivery Window **
DEL - Delivered Time

flattened_text: The `DeliveryTime` object contains information about delivery times for a package. It includes properties such as `startTime`, `endTime`, and `type`. The `startTime` and `endTime` properties represent the start and end times of the delivery, while the `type` property indicates the type of delivery detail (e.g., End of Day, Commit Time, Estimated Delivery Window, Confirmed Delivery Window, Imminent Delivery Window, Delivered Time). The times are in 24-hour format (HHMMSS).
This defines a data structure for package dimensions, including height, length, width, and unit of measurement.
This defines an "Error" object with properties for a code and a message, both of type string.
This API endpoint is called "InquireNumbers" and is used to retrieve a list of inquiry numbers. The response will be an array of strings containing the inquiry numbers.

This defines a "Location" object with properties for an address and a Site Location Indicator Code (SLIC). The address property references a separate schema for address details, while the SLIC property is a string type with an example value of '8566'.

Milestones.title: Milestones
Milestones.description: The list of milestones associated with the package. Milestones will be returned in chronological order, with the oldest first and most recent/future milestones last.

category.description: The milestone category. This will be present only when a milestone is in a COMPLETE state.

current.description: The indication if the milestone represents the current state of the package. Valid values: 'true' this milestone is the current state of the package.  'false' this milestone is not current.

description.description: The milestone description. Note: this is not translated at this time and is returned in US English.

linkedActivity.description: The 0-based index of the activity that triggered this milestone. This will be returned only when a milestone is in a COMPLETE state. For example the most recent activity on the response is index 0.

state.description: The milestone state. Valid values: 'This milestone has already occurred'/'This milestone has not yet been completed'.

flattened_text: The "Milestones" object contains a list of milestones related to a package. Milestones are ordered chronologically, with the oldest first. Each milestone includes details such as category, code, current status, description, linked activity, state, and sub-milestones. The category is only present for completed milestones. Descriptions are in US English and some details are only available for completed milestones.

additionalAttributes.description: The list of additional attributes that may be associated with the package. Presence of any element indicates the package has that attribute.

additionalServices.description: The list of additional services that may be associated with the package. Presence of any element indicates that the package has that service.

isSmartPackage.description: Indicator of whether the package is a smart package

packageCount.description: The total number of packages in the shipment. Note that this number may be greater than the number of returned packages in the response. In such cases subsequent calls are needed to get additional packages.

statusDescription.description: The activity status description. Note: this field will be translated based on the locale provided in the request.

suppressionIndicators.description: Contains values which signify that certain data should be suppressed or hidden. Valid values: Tracking activity details should be hidden. Note: this is mainly intended for use by UPS.com applications.

ucixStatus.description: This indicator provides UCIX (UPS Customer Information Exchange) status Valid values: 'O' means open. 'C' means closed.

flattened_text: This document describes the properties of a package, including information like access point details, activities, additional attributes and services, tracking numbers, delivery status, dimensions, and weight. It also covers details like package count, payment information, and reference numbers. The package status, description, and suppression indicators are included, along with UCIX status for UPS Customer Information Exchange.

PackageAddress.title: PackageAddress
PackageAddress.description: The container array that has all the addresses associated with the package, such as the ship from (shipper), ship to (consignee), and delivery addresses

attentionName.description: The specific name of an individual associated with the address segment.

flattened_text: The `PackageAddress` object contains various addresses related to a package, including the sender, recipient, and delivery addresses. It includes fields for the address details, attention name, recipient name, and address type (e.g., origin/destination).

PaymentInformation.title: PaymentInformation
PaymentInformation.description: The container array that has all the payment information associated with the package, such as 'Collect on Delivery payment'.

amount.description: The payment amount. This value will contain the amount in dollars and cents, separated by a period (.) Example: '1025.50'.9

currency.description: The payment currency code (see API codes for possible values).

id.description: The payment internal ID. This may be used in other systems to retrieve additional information on the payment.

paid.description: The indication for whether the payment is paid or not. Valid values: 'true' the payment is paid. 'false' the payment is not paid.

flattened_text: The PaymentInformation object contains details about the payment associated with a package. It includes the payment amount, currency, internal ID, payment status, payment method, and payment type. The amount is in dollars and cents, currency is a code, and paid indicates if the payment is complete. The ID can be used to retrieve more payment information from other systems. The payment method and type are also specified.

ReferenceNumber.title: ReferenceNumber
ReferenceNumber.description: The list of reference numbers associated with the package.

type.description: The type of reference number. Specifies how the reference number is associated with the package.

flattened_text: This object represents a reference number associated with a package. It includes the reference number itself (e.g., ShipRef123) and the type of reference number (e.g., SHIPMENT).
The response object contains a reference to the ErrorResponse schema and is of type object.
This defines an "ErrorResponse" object that contains an array of "errors" referencing the "Error" schema. It is used to structure error responses in the API.

Service.title: Service
Service.description: The container which has the package service information.

description.description: The service name description. Note that this field will be translated based on the locale provided in the request.

flattened_text: This object represents a service with information about its code, description, and level code. The service name code, description, and level code are all strings. The description field can be translated based on the locale provided in the request.

userRelation.description:
The relationship of the user to the package(s) in the shipment. No value means that the user has no relationship to the package. Note that this check is only done when the request contains the 'Username' and package rights checking is performed. Valid values:
'MYC_HOME' - My Choice for Home
'MYC_BUS_OUTBOUND' - My Choice for Business Outbound
'MYC_BUS_INBOUND' - My Choice for Business Inbound
'SHIPPER' - Shipper

flattened_text: This API defines a "Shipment" object with properties including an inquiry number, package details, user relation to the package(s) in the shipment, and any warnings associated with the shipment. The user relation property specifies the user's relationship to the package(s) and includes valid values like 'MYC_HOME' for My Choice for Home. The warnings property lists any warnings related to the shipment.

Signature.title: Signature
Signature.description: Container with all the signature information associated to the package being delivered.

image.description: The base64 encoded string representation of the signature image. Note: This is considered sensitive data and may only be returned for a user that has rights to the package.

flattened_text: This object contains the signature information for a delivered package. It includes the base64 encoded string of the signature image. Access to this sensitive data is restricted to authorized users.

Status.title: Status
Status.description: The container which has the current package status

description.description: The current status description. Note that this field will be translated based on the locale provided in the request.
description.example: Your package was released by the customs agency.

simplifiedTextDescription.description: The current status in simplified text. This is a supplementary description providing additional information on the status of the package. Note that this field will be translated based on the locale provided in the request.

statusCode.description: The activity package detail status code see API Codes for possible values.

flattened_text: This object represents the current status of a package. It includes the status code, description, simplified text description, status code, and type. The description fields will be translated based on the request locale. The status code corresponds to possible API codes.

SubMilestone.title: SubMilestone
SubMilestone.description: The sub-milestone container containing information on a child milestone. Will be present only if a child milestone exists.

flattened_text: A "SubMilestone" is a container for details about a child milestone. It includes a category property that specifies the sub-milestone's category. This container is only present if there is a child milestone.
This defines a response object for tracking API requests. It includes a property called "trackResponse" that references the schema for the actual tracking response data.
The `TrackResponse` object contains an array of shipment items, each referencing the `Shipment` schema.
This OpenAPI schema defines a "Warning" object with properties for a warning code and message.

Weight.title: Weight
Weight.description: The weight container for the package.

unitOfMeasurement.description: The weight units of measurement. Valid values: 'LBS' - pounds. 'KGS' - kilograms.

weight.description: The weight units of measurement. Valid values: 'LBS' - pounds. 'KGS' - kilograms.

flattened_text: This object defines the weight of a package. It includes the unit of measurement (either pounds or kilograms) and the weight value.

info.title: WorldEase Shipment Management API v1
info.description:
## Purpose
The WorldEase Shipment Management API facilitates the consolidation of packages into a single shipment to reduce the brokerage fees and streamline international shipping processes. It offers users the ability to manage the shipment lifecycle including aggregating individual packages, closing out shipments once consolidation is completed and managing master and child shipments with options to delete as necessary.

flattened_text: The WorldEase Shipment Management API v1 helps users consolidate packages into a single shipment to save on fees and simplify international shipping. It allows managing the entire shipment process, from combining packages to closing out shipments. Users can handle master and child shipments and delete them when needed.

version.description: Indicates WorldEase Shipment Management API to display the new release features
Indicates WorldEase Shipment Management API to display the new release features

flattened_text: This OpenAPI document defines two server environments for integrating with UPS APIs. The "Customer Integration Environment" server is for testing and uses the URL "https://wwwcie.ups.com/api/ship/{version}". The "Production" server is for live usage and has the URL "https://onlinetools.ups.com/api/ship/{version}". Both servers support the "v1" version of the WorldEase Shipment Management API, showcasing new release features.

post.description: Finalizes the shipment process by marking a package or set of packages as ready for dispatch, effectively ending the consolidation stage.

parameters.name: shipment-gccn
parameters.description: The unique identifier of the shipment to close Out. It also known as GCCN.

parameters.name: version
parameters.description: Indicates WorldEase Shipment Management API to display the new release features

400.description: Missing required values or incorrect values or validation fails

flattened_text: This endpoint finalizes the shipment process by marking a package or set of packages as ready for dispatch. It requires the unique shipment identifier (GCCN) and specific headers for transaction details. The API also supports versioning for new features. Upon successful closure, it returns a label and transaction ID. Possible responses include request accepted, missing values, unauthorized access, and not found errors. The endpoint is secured using OAuth2 and falls under the "World Ease Shipment Management - Shipment" category.

delete.description: Deletes the specified master shipment from the system. Once deleted system cannot be recovered

parameters.name: shipment-gccn
parameters.description: The unique identifier of the shipment to delete the master shipment. It is also known as GCCN.

parameters.name: version
parameters.description: Indicates WorldEase Shipment Management API to display the new release features

value.message: The Delete request has been done successfully for the following GCCN - 12345678901

400.description: Missing required values or incorrect values or validation fails

flattened_text: This endpoint allows you to delete a specific master shipment from the system permanently. You need to provide the unique identifier (GCCN) of the shipment to be deleted. Additionally, you must include transaction information and specify the API version. The response will confirm the successful deletion or provide error messages for missing or incorrect data. This operation requires OAuth2 authentication.

delete.description: This is used to delete the child shipment record from the database

parameters.name: shipment-gccn
parameters.description: The unique identifier of the shipment to identify the master shipment. It is also known as GCCN.

parameters.name: trackingNumber
parameters.description: The identifier of the shipment to identify the child shipment. It is also known as 1Z Tracking Number.

parameters.name: version
parameters.description: Indicates WorldEase Shipment Management API to display the new release features

value.message: The Delete request has been done successfully for the following 1Z tracking Number- 1Z9991450419000046

400.description: Missing required values or incorrect values or validation fails

flattened_text: This endpoint allows you to delete a child shipment record from the database. You need to provide the master shipment identifier (GCCN) and the child shipment identifier (1Z Tracking Number). Additionally, you must include custom transaction IDs and specify the API version. Upon successful deletion, you will receive a confirmation message. Possible error responses include missing or incorrect values, unauthorized access, and not found errors for GCCN or tracking numbers. This operation requires OAuth2 authentication.

OAuth2.description:
Find your Client ID and Secret on your app info page. 
  1. Select "Try It" 
  2. In the Security section enter your Client ID and Secret 
  3. Select "Request Token"
  4. Enter any additional information in the Body and Parameters sections
  5. Select "Send" to execute your API request"

flattened_text: The OAuth2 security scheme allows you to authenticate your API requests using a Client ID and Secret. To get started, find your credentials on your app info page. Follow the steps to enter your Client ID and Secret, request a token, and execute your API request. The token URL for authentication is provided.

shipperAccountNumber.description: This is the unique account number associated with the Shipper. It is also known as UPS Shipper Account Number

flattened_text: This API endpoint requires a shipper's unique account number, also known as the UPS Shipper Account Number, to be included in the request. The account number must be provided as a string in the request body.

label.description: This will contain master shipment label

opTyp.description: The is the output type in which label is generated

lblNmbr.description: The label number assigned to this label

flattened_text: The `PostResponse` object contains information about a shipment label. It includes the base64 encoded label image (`lblData`), the label number (`lblNmbr`), and the output type (`opTyp`) such as PNG, GIF, PDF, etc. It also references a custom transaction ID (`transId`). Both `transId` and `label` are required fields.

code.description: Identifies the success or failure of the transaction. 1 = Successful

flattened_text: This response object is returned when a deletion operation is successful. It includes a code indicating success (1 for successful) and a message confirming the successful deletion. Both code and message are required fields in the response.

errors.description: error payload - array containing one or more Errors

flattened_text: This defines the structure of an error response, which includes an array of error objects. The response must include at least one error object.

code.description: The code is specific to the error

message.description: The message that associated with the above error code

flattened_text: This defines an "Error" object with two properties: "code" for a specific error code and "message" for the corresponding error message. The object is of type "object."

CustomTransactionId.description: Client generated id which is treated as the Transaction ID

flattened_text: This field allows clients to create a unique transaction ID using a 32-character string of letters and numbers, including hyphens. The example provided is "4ce27ff5-8e17-4797-a8c1-089796db".

CustomTransactionSrc.description: An identifier of the client/source application that is making the request.Length 512

flattened_text: This field, CustomTransactionSrc, is used to identify the client or source application making the request. It can be up to 512 characters long and should be a string. An example value is "SAM".

info.title: Pickup
info.description:
Using the Pickup API, applications can schedule pickups, manage previously scheduled pickups, or cancel previously scheduled pickups. # Reference - Business Rules - Appendix - Errors

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

flattened_text: The Pickup API allows applications to schedule, manage, and cancel pickups. You can access business rules, appendix, and error information through the provided links. Explore UPS APIs with example requests using Postman and find sample applications on GitHub.
This OpenAPI specification defines two server URLs: one for the Customer Integration Environment at https://wwwcie.ups.com/api and one for Production at https://onlinetools.ups.com/api.

post.description: Using the POST operation of the pickuptype endpoint within the Pickup API, users can request rates for UPS on-demand package pickup. The endpoint allows users to specify pickup details like address, date/time, and other options, and returns pricing information for booking that pickup.

flattened_text: This API endpoint allows users to check the status of UPS shipments scheduled for pickup. Users can retrieve information such as received, dispatched, completed, or canceled shipments by providing their account number. The endpoint requires specifying the version of the API and the type of pickup (oncall, smart, or both). The endpoint supports both GET and POST operations for different functionalities related to UPS pickup services.

delete.description: Using the CancelBy endpoint of the Pickup API, users can request cancellation of a UPS on-demand package pickup. When the PRN (pickup request number), transaction ID, and the transaction source are supplied as required parameters, the endpoint returns confirmation that the pickup has been cancelled.

parameters.name: transId
parameters.description: An identifier unique to the request. Length 32

parameters.name: transactionSrc
parameters.description: An identifier of the client/source application that is making the request.Length 512

parameters.name: Prn
parameters.description:
The pickup equest number (PRN) generated by 
UPS pickup system.
Required if CancelBy = prn.Length 26

parameters.name: CancelBy
parameters.description: Valid Values: 01 = AccountNumber, 02 = PRN

parameters.name: version
parameters.description:
Version of API.

Valid values:
- v2409

flattened_text:
**Summary:**

The `/shipments/{version}/pickup/{CancelBy}` endpoint allows users to cancel a UPS on-demand package pickup using the Pickup API. Users must provide the PRN, transaction ID, and transaction source as parameters to confirm the cancellation. The endpoint supports different cancellation methods based on the `CancelBy` parameter. The API version `v2409` is required for this operation. Various responses are returned based on the success or failure of the cancellation request, including `200` for success, `400` for an invalid request, `401` for unauthorized requests, `403` for blocked merchants, and `429` for rate limit exceeded. The endpoint is secured using OAuth2 and falls under the `Pickup` tag.

flattened_text:
To use OAuth2 for authentication, find your Client ID and Secret on your app info page. Follow these steps:

1. Select "Try It".
2. Enter your Client ID and Secret in the Security section.
3. Click "Request Token".
4. Add any extra information in the Body and Parameters sections.
5. Click "Send" to run your API request.

OAuth2 uses client credentials and the token URL is at https://wwwcie.ups.com/security/v1/oauth/token. The authentication method is client_secret_basic.

This API endpoint, `PICKUPRequestWrapper`, is used to send a request for pickup rates. It contains a single property, `PickupRateRequest`, which references the schema for pickup rate requests. The `PickupRateRequest` property is required and must be included in the request.

This response wrapper contains a single property called PickupRateResponse, which refers to the PickupRateResponse schema. The PickupRateResponse property is required and the wrapper is represented as an object in XML with the name PickupRateResponse.

AlternateAddressIndicator.description:
Indicates if the pickup address is different than the address specified in the customer's profile.  
Valid values:
Y = Alternate address
N = Original pickup address (default)

ServiceDateOption.description:
Indicates the pickup timeframe.
- 01 = Same-Day Pickup
- 02 = Future-Day Pickup
- 03 = A Specific-Day Pickup

If 03 is selected, then PickupDate, EarliestReadyTime, and LatestClosetime must be specified.

RateChartType.description:
Rate Type with which pickup is rated. Possible RateChart values for different regions will be:

US 48 origin:
1 – Daily Rates
3 – Standard List Rates
4 – Retail Rates.

 Alaska/Hawaii origin:
1 – Daily Rates
3 – Standard List Rates
4 – Retail Rates.

All Other origins:
1 – Rates
5 - Regional Rates
6 - General List Rates.

3 and 4 do not apply

TaxInformationIndicator.description:
Indicates whether to return detailed taxes for on-callpickups.
Valid values:
- Y = Rate this pickup with taxes
- N = Do not rate this pickup with taxes (default)

UserLevelDiscountIndicator.description:
Indicates whether to return user level promo discount for the on-callpickups. 
Valid values:
Y = Rate this pickup with user level promo discount
N = Do not rate this pickup with user level promo discount(default)

PickupRateRequest.description: This request is used to rate an on-callpickup.

flattened_text: The `PickupRateRequest` is a request used to calculate the rate for an on-call pickup. It includes information such as the pickup address, pickup date, rate chart type, service date option, shipper account, tax information indicator, and user level discount indicator. Some fields have specific valid values and requirements. The request must include the service date option, pickup address, request, and alternate address indicator.

SubVersion.description:
When UPS introduces new elements in the response that are not associated with new request elements, Subversion is used. This ensures backward compatibility.

To get such elements you need to have the right Subversion. The value of the subversion is explained in the Response element Description. Supported values: 1607, 1707,2007

Example: Itemized Charges are returned only when the Subversion element is present and greater than or equal to '1601'. 

Format: YYMM = Year and month of the release.
Example: 1601 = 2016 January

flattened_text:
This element, `PickupRateRequest_Request`, is a common structure used across all services. It includes three properties: `RequestOption`, `SubVersion`, and `TransactionReference`. 

- `RequestOption` is a string with a length between 1 and 15 characters, not used for pick up.
- `SubVersion` is a string that indicates the version of the response elements for backward compatibility. Supported values are 1607, 1707, and 2007.
- `TransactionReference` refers to another schema for transaction details.

The element is of type object and is named `Request` in XML.

CustomerContext.description: The CustomerContext information that is echoed back during response.

flattened_text: This object, Request_TransactionReference, contains CustomerContext information that will be included in the response. The CustomerContext field is a string with a maximum length of 512 characters.

AccountNumber.description: UPS account number.  Shipper's (requester of the pickup) UPS account number

AccountCountryCode.description:
Country code as defined by ISO-3166.
Refer to Country or Territory Codes in the Appendix for valid values.

flattened_text: This object represents the shipper's account information needed for requesting a pickup. It includes the country code (ISO-3166) and the UPS account number. Both fields are required and have specific length constraints.

AddressLine.description:
Detailed street address. 
For Jan. 2010 release, only one AddressLine is allowed.

PostalCode.description: Postal code for countries with postal codes.

CountryCode.description:
Upper-case two-char long country code as defined by ISO-3166. 
Refer to Country or Territory Codes in the Appendix for valid values.

ResidentialIndicator.description:
Indicates if the pickup address is commerical or residential.
Valid values:
Y = Residential address
N = Non-residential (Commercial) address (default)

PickupRateRequest_PickupAddress.description: The address to pickup the packages

flattened_text: This object defines the pickup address for packages. It includes fields for the detailed street address, city, country code, postal code, residential or commercial indicator, and state or province. The address must include the state/province, residential indicator, postal code, city, and country code.

CloseTime.description:
The latest local close time. Format: HHmm
- Hour: 0-23
- Minute: 0-59

ReadyTime.description:
The earliest local ready Time. Format: HHmm
- Hour: 0-23
- Minute: 0-59

PickupDate.description:
The specific local pickup date. Format: yyyyMMdd
- yyyy = Year Applicable
- MM = 01-12
- dd = 01-31

PickupRateRequest_PickupDateInfo.description:
Required if the ServiceDateOption is: 
03 A Specific-Day Pickup

flattened_text: This object, PickupRateRequest_PickupDateInfo, is required when selecting a specific-day pickup service date option. It includes properties for CloseTime (latest close time), PickupDate (specific pickup date), and ReadyTime (earliest ready time). The properties have specific formats for time and date. The object is required and must include ReadyTime, CloseTime, and PickupDate.

WeekendServiceTerritoryIndicator.description:
Indicates if the pickup address qualifies for WST (Weekend Service Territory). Returned if the pickup date is Saturday and subversion greater or equal to 1607. Valid Values:
- Y = WST
- N = Non-WST

flattened_text: The `PickupRateResponse` object represents the response for rating an on-call pickup. It includes properties such as `RateResult`, `Response`, and `WeekendServiceTerritory`. The `WeekendServiceTerritoryIndicator` property indicates if the pickup address qualifies for Weekend Service Territory (WST) based on the pickup date and subversion. The `Response` and `RateResult` properties are required.
This response container includes an alert, response status, and transaction reference. The response status is required. The container is in XML format and allows for a maximum of one alert.

Code.description:
Identifies the success of the transaction.
- 1=Success
- 0=failed

Description.description: Describes Response Status Code.

flattened_text: This defines a response status container with two properties: Code (identifying transaction success) and Description (describing the status code). The Code property is a string with a maximum length of 1, representing success (1) or failure (0). The Description property is a string with a maximum length of 35. Both properties are required in the response.

Code.description: Warning code returned by the system.

Description.description: Warning messages returned by the system.

Response_Alert.description: Alert Container. There can be zero to many alert containers with code and description.

flattened_text: This defines an "Alert" object that can contain warning code and messages from the system. Each alert can have one code (up to 10 characters) and one description (up to 150 characters). Both code and description are required fields.

CustomerContext.description: The CustomerContext information that is echoed back during response.

flattened_text: This response object contains the transaction reference information. It includes the CustomerContext field, which echoes back customer information in the response. The CustomerContext field is a string with a maximum length of 512 characters.

RateType.description:
Indicates the pickup is rated as same-day or future-day pickup.
- SD = Same-day Pickup
- FD = Future-day Pickup

CurrencyCode.description: IATA currency codes for the pickup charge. Such as USD

GrandTotalOfAllCharge.description: The grand total of each charge and applied tax.

GrandTotalOfAllIncentedCharge.description: The grand total of each incented charge and applied tax. Only present if 1. UserLevelDiscountIndicator = Y and User Level Promotion is applied to the pickup or 2 .if any incentive rate is applied to the pickup and SubVersion on the request is greater than or equal to 1707.

PreTaxTotalCharge.description: Total of charges before taxes. Only present when tax details requested in input.

PreTaxTotalIncentedCharge.description: Total of incented charges before taxes. Only present if 1. UserLevelDiscountIndicator = Y and User Level Promotion is applied to the pickup or 2 .if any incentive rate is applied to the pickup and SubVersion on the request is greater than or equal to 1707.

PickupRateResponse_RateResult.description: The result of rating an on-callpickup.

flattened_text: The `PickupRateResponse_RateResult` object represents the result of rating an on-call pickup. It includes details such as the currency code, total charges, pre-tax charges, rate type (same-day or future-day), tax charges, and total taxes. Some fields are conditionally present based on user-level discounts, promotions, or incentive rates. The object is required to have a currency code and is structured as an object named `RateResult`.

ChargeCode.description:
Indicates the general charge type
- A = ACCESSORIAL TYPE
- B = BASE CHARGE TYPE
- S = SURCHARGE TYPE

ChargeDescription.description:
Description of each charge.The possible descriptions are:
- BASE CHARGE
- EXTENDED AREA SURCHARGE
- FUEL SURCHARGE
- REMOTE AREA SURCHARGE
- RESIDENTIAL SURCHARGE
- SATURDAY ON-CALL STOP CHARGE

IncentedAmount.description: Monetary value of the incented charge. Only present if 1. UserLevelDiscountIndicator = Y and User Level Promotion is applied to the pickup or 2 .if any incentive rate is applied to the pickup and SubVersion on the request is greater than or equal to 1707.

TaxAmount.description: Monetary value of the tax if apply.

flattened_text: This data structure represents detailed charges for a shipping rate. It includes properties such as the monetary value of the charge, charge code indicating the type of charge, charge description, incented amount if applicable, and tax amount. The charge code specifies whether the charge is an accessorial, base, or surcharge type. The charge description provides details about the charge type. The incented amount is included if certain conditions are met. The tax amount is the monetary value of any applicable tax.

Type.description:
Type of Tax code. 
Valid values: ALV, BTW, DDS, DDV, DPH, FPA, GST, IVA, IVA1, IVA2, IVA3, KM, MOMS, MWST, PDV, PST, PVM, PVN, QST, TVA, VAT, VSK.

MonetaryValue.description: Monetary value of the tax.

RateResult_TaxCharges.description: Container to hold taxes when, detailed taxes are request via RateTaxIndicator.

flattened_text: This object, RateResult_TaxCharges, holds detailed tax information when requested via RateTaxIndicator. It includes properties for the monetary value of the tax and the type of tax code, with specific valid values. Both the Type and MonetaryValue properties are required.

SatWST.description:
Indicates if the pickup address qualifies for WST (Weekend Service Territory). Returned if the pickup date is Saturday and subversion greater or equal to 2007. Valid Values:
- Y = Saturday WST
- N = Non-Saturday WST

SunWST.description:
Indicates if the pickup address qualifies for WST (Weekend Service Territory). Returned if the pickup date is Sunday and subversion greater or equal to 2007. Valid Values:
- Y = Sunday WST
- N = Non-Sunday WST

PickupRateResponse_WeekendServiceTerrito.description: WeekendServiceTerritory Container.Returned if the  subversion greater or equal to 2007.

flattened_text: This response provides information about whether a pickup address qualifies for Weekend Service Territory (WST) on Saturdays and Sundays. It includes properties for Saturday WST and Sunday WST, with valid values of Y for qualifying and N for non-qualifying. The response is returned for subversions equal to or greater than 2007. The response is structured as an object named WeekendServiceTerritory and requires both Saturday and Sunday WST properties.

PaymentMethod.description:
The payment method to pay for this on call pickup.
00 = No payment needed
01 = Pay by shipper account
03 = Pay by charge card
04 = Pay by 1Z tracking number
05 = Pay by check or money order
06 = Cash(applicable only for these countries - BE,FR,DE,IT,MX,NL,PL,ES,GB,CZ,HU,FI,NO)
07=Pay by PayPal
Refer to Appendix # for valid payment methods for CZ, HU, FI and NO
  For countries and (or) zip codes where pickup is free of charge, please submit 00, means no payment needed as payment method. 
- If 01 is the payment method, then ShipperAccountNumber and ShipperAccount CountryCode must be provided.
- If 03 is selected, then CreditCard information should be provided.
- If 04 is selected, then the shipper agreed to pay for the pickup packages.
- If 05 is selected, then the shipper will pay for the pickup packages with a check or money order.

Certain fields are required, such as pickup date, address, payment method, and pickup pieces. The request is in object format and is named PickupCreationRequest.

To get such elements you need to have the right Subversion. The value of the subversion is explained in the Response element Description. Supported values: 1607, 1707,2007

The TransactionReference field references another schema for transaction details.

PickupCreationRequest_Shipper.description:
On-call pickup shipper or requestor information.   Must provide when choose to pay the pickup by shipper account number, BillThirdParty account number, or BillReceiver account number. 
It is optional if the shipper chooses any other payment method. However, it is highly recommended to provide if available.

It includes the AccountCountryCode (ISO-3166 country code) and AccountNumber (UPS account number) properties. Both properties are required. The AccountCountryCode is a 2-character string, and the AccountNumber is a string between 6 and 10 characters long.

CardHolderName.description: Charge card holder name. If the name is not provided, defaults to "No Name Provided".

CardType.description:
Charge card type. Valid values:
- 01 = American Express
- 03 = Discover
- 04 = Mastercard
- 06 = VISA  Discover card Pickup country US only.

CardNumber.description: Charge card number.  For Privileged clients, this element must be tokenized card number.

Credit card expiration date.
Format: yyyyMM
yyyy = 4 digit year, valid value current year - 10 years.
MM = 2 digit month, valid values 01-12

SecurityCode.description:
Three or four digits that can be found either on top of credit card number or on the back of credit card. 
Number of digits varies for different type of credit card.  Valid values are 3 or 4 digits.
Security code is required if credit card information is provided.

Shipper_ChargeCard.description: Container for Charge Card payment method  Required if Payment method is 03. Credit/Charge card payment is valid for US, CA, PR and GB origin pickups.

flattened_text: The Shipper ChargeCard object is used for storing credit card payment information for shipments originating in the US, Canada, Puerto Rico, and Great Britain. It includes fields for the cardholder's name, card number, card type, expiration date, security code, and card address. The card number must be between 9 and 16 characters long, and the card type must be one of the specified values (American Express, Discover, Mastercard, VISA). The expiration date must be in the format yyyyMM, representing the year and month. The security code can be 3 or 4 digits and is required when providing credit card information.

AddressLine.description: Address Lines of the credit card billing address.  Max of three address lines can be provided.

StateProvince.description: Charge card billing State province code

PostalCode.description: Charge card billing address postal code.  This is a required field for postal countries.

CountryCode.description:
Charge card billing address country or territory code defined by ISO-3166.

Upper-case two letter string. For Discover card it should be US.

ChargeCard_CardAddress.description: Container to hold the Charge card address.

flattened_text: This data structure, "ChargeCard_CardAddress," is used to store the billing address associated with a charge card. It includes fields for the address lines, city, country code, postal code, and state or province. The country code must be in ISO-3166 format (two uppercase letters). The address lines can have a maximum of three lines, and each line can be up to 35 characters long. The city, country code, postal code, and state/province fields have specific length restrictions. The country code field is required.

CloseTime.description:
Pickup location's local close time.
- User provided Close Time must be later than the Earliest Allowed Customer Close Time.
- Earliest Allowed Customer Close Time is defined by UPS pickup operation system.
- CloseTime minus ReadyTime must be greater than the LeadTime.
- LeadTime is determined by UPS pickup operation system. LeadTime is the minimum amount of time UPS requires between customer's request for a pickup and driver arriving at the location for the pickup.

Format: HHmm
- Hour: 0-23
- Minute: 0-59

ReadyTime.description:
Pickup location's local ready time. 
ReadyTime means the time when your shipment(s) can be ready for UPS to pick up. 
- User provided ReadyTime must be earlier than CallByTime. 
- CallByTime is determined by UPS pickup operation system. CallByTime is the Latest time a Customer can call UPS or self-serve on UPS.com and complete a Pickup Request and UPS can still make the Pickup service request. 
- If ReadyTime is earlier than current local time, UPS uses the current local time as the ReadyTime.  Format: HHmm
Hour: 0-23
Minute: 0-59

PickupDate.description:
Local pickup date of the location. Format: yyyyMMdd
- yyyy = Year Appliable
- MM = 01–12
- dd = 01–31

PickupCreationRequest_PickupDateInfo.description: The container of desired pickup date

flattened_text: This object, `PickupCreationRequest_PickupDateInfo`, contains information about scheduling a pickup. It includes the local pickup date, the location's ready time, and the location's close time. The `PickupDate` property specifies the date in the format `yyyyMMdd`. The `ReadyTime` property indicates when the shipment is ready for pickup, and it must be before the `CallByTime`. The `CloseTime` property represents the location's closing time and must meet specific criteria related to lead time.

StateProvince.description: State or province for postal countries; county for Ireland (IE) and district code for Hong Kong (HK)

- Barrio for Mexico (MX)
- Urbanization for Puerto Rico (PR)
- Shire for United Kingdom (UK)
