info.title: Delivery Intercept® API
info.description: With the UPS Delivery Intercept® API, a shipper can manage the delivery details of their shipment, prior to delivery. # Business Values **Key Business Values:** - elimination of manually processing customer requests - acceptance of requests later in the delivery process Product Info # CIE Behavior The Delivery Intercept API will return a stubbed success response if the correct data is used for a given endpoint. The static data that is valid for each of the endpoints is in the table below: | Endpoint | transId | trackingNumber | |------------|-------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------| | /charges | SIICharges | 1Z4096YY0316914058 | /willcall | SIIWillcall | 1Z4096YY0316914058 | /return | SIIReturn | 1Z4096YY0316914058 | /reschedule | SIIReschedule | 1Z4096YY0316914058 | /redirect/address | SIIRedirect | 1Z4096YY0316914058 | /cancel | SIICancel | 1Z4096YY0316914058

flattened_text: The Delivery Intercept API by UPS allows shippers to manage shipment details before delivery. Key benefits include automating customer requests and accepting requests later in the delivery process. The API provides stubbed success responses for specific endpoints. For more information, visit the [Product Info](https://developer.ups.com/api/reference/deliveryintercept/product-info) page.

This OpenAPI specification defines two server environments for UPS API: Customer Integration Environment and Production. Both environments support version "v2" of the delivery intercept API. The URLs for accessing the API in each environment are provided.

post.description: Obtains intercept charges specified by the inquiry type.

errors.message: Failure due to input validation error
Package address token does not match any tokens in the user's profile.

flattened_text: This endpoint allows you to retrieve intercept charges based on the inquiry type using a POST request. It requires various parameters and a JSON request body with specific information. The response includes charge details and status information. Different HTTP status codes indicate success, validation errors, authentication requirements, or system errors. The endpoint is available in both a Customer Integration Environment and Production environment.

post.summary: redirect a package to a Customer center for pickup.
post.description: Request your package to be held at or returned to a UPS facility where the receiver may claim the same-day.

errors.message: Failure due to input validation error
Package address token does not match any tokens in the user's profile.

flattened_text: This endpoint allows you to request a package to be held at or returned to a UPS facility for same-day pickup. The request includes various details like tracking number, delivery date, requester contact info, and special instructions. The response provides information about the UPS facility where the package can be picked up. The endpoint supports successful responses, validation errors, authentication requirements, and system errors. It falls under the "Delivery Intercept" category.

post.summary: redirect the package back to the sender
post.description: Return the package to the original shipper prior to delivery.

errors.message: Failure due to input validation error
Package address token does not match any tokens in the user's profile.

flattened_text: This endpoint allows you to return a package to the original shipper before delivery. It requires various parameters and a JSON request body with specific information. The response includes success or error messages based on the request. The purpose is to redirect the package back to the sender.

post.summary: change to a new delivery date in the future.
post.description: Have the package delivered to the original address but on a different day in the future.

errors.message: Failure due to input validation error
Package address token does not match any tokens in the user's profile.

flattened_text: This endpoint allows users to reschedule a package delivery to the original address but on a different future date. Users can provide various details such as delivery date, tracking number, contact information, and special instructions. The response includes information about the success of the rescheduling request. The endpoint supports error handling for validation errors, authentication requirements, and system errors. It falls under the "Delivery Intercept" category.

post.summary: Submission to request a new delivery address.
post.description: Deliver to a different address than on the label originally created for the shipment.

errors.message: Failure due to input validation error
Package address token does not match any tokens in the user's profile.

flattened_text: This endpoint allows users to submit a request to deliver a shipment to a different address than the one originally specified. Users can provide details such as the tracking number, new address, and contact information. The response includes information about the success of the request, any validation errors, authentication requirements, or system errors. The endpoint is tagged under "Delivery Intercept."

post.summary: cancel an existing Delivery Intercept request
post.description: Cancel a previously applied intercept on the package.

errors.message: Failure due to input validation error
Package address token does not match any tokens in the user's profile.

flattened_text: This endpoint allows you to cancel a previously requested delivery intercept on a package. It requires specific parameters and a JSON request body with details like tracking number and requester information. The responses include success and error messages, with details on charges, status, and validation errors. The endpoint summary is to cancel an existing Delivery Intercept request and is tagged under Delivery Intercept.

OAuth2.description:
Find your Client ID and Secret on your app info page. 
  1. Select "Try It"

  3. Select "Request Token"
  4. Enter any additional information in the Body and Parameters sections
  5. Select "Send" to execute your API request"

flattened_text: The OAuth2 security scheme allows you to authenticate your API requests using a Client ID and Secret. To get started, find your credentials on your app info page. Follow the steps to enter your Client ID and Secret, request a token, and execute your API request. The token URL for authentication is provided.

flattened_text: The `AddressBookEntry` object contains properties for storing information about a customer address entry. It includes fields for address details, a nickname, contact name, email address, IMS entry number, name or company name, phone extension, and phone number. These properties are used when creating, updating, or retrieving entries in an IMS address book. The `addressInfo` field is required if `imsAddrIdentifier` is not present. The `emailAddress`, `phoneExt`, and `phoneNumber` fields have specific format requirements.

activitySLICNumber.description:
When provided, the Will Call center lookup will be done using this identifier. The lookup will only be done using the postalCode
when this field is blank.

streetAddressParsedIndicator.description: Set it to true when clients send in parsed street address for redirects.

Parsed street address object, includes streetName, steetSuffix, streetPrefix, streetType and streetNumber.
Required when streetAddressParsedIndicator is TRUE.

streetName.description:
street level validation of an Address At least one of the street fields is required when streetAddressParsedIndicator
is set to TRUE in AddressInformation.

flattened_text: The `AddressInformation` object contains details about a physical address. It includes fields for street address, city, country code, postal code, state, and phone number. The object also has properties for first name, last name, and full name. Additionally, there are fields for parsed street address components like street name, number, prefix, suffix, and type. The `streetAddressParsedIndicator` field is used to indicate if the street address is parsed. The `city` and `countryCode` fields are required.

flattened_text: The `ChargesInfo` object contains various properties related to shipping charges and details. It includes information such as accessorial charges, handling indicators, currency, payment details, service codes, package weight, taxes, and tracking numbers. Some properties indicate if charges are paid by the shipper or a third party. The object also covers tax disclaimers, service descriptions, and estimated delivery dates. The `ChargesInfo` object is required to have a `chargeCurrency` property and is structured as an object with multiple nested properties.

It includes information about charges applied, errors that occurred, transaction status, success indicator, transaction ID for identification, and warnings. Key properties include `chargeInfo`, `errors`, `statusCode`, `statusMsg`, `success`, `transactionId`, and `warnings`. The object is required to have `transactionId`, `statusCode`, and `success` properties.

Will only be returned if notificationRequestType is DBD email or DBD phone. Indicates if My Choice is supported in the
package's ship to country. 

| CODE  | DESCRIPTION                                     |
| :--:  | :--                                             |

flattened_text:
This response object includes two properties: 
1. `addrToken`: A token linked to the tracking number and one of the user's enrollments. It is a string with a maximum length of 32 characters.
2. `myChoiceCountry`: This property is returned only if the notification request type is DBD email or DBD phone. It indicates if My Choice is supported in the package's destination country. The value can be '0' for no support, or '1' for support.

The `MyChoiceConsolidatorError` object includes properties for error code, error message, and error source. The error code is a string with a maximum length of 4 characters, while the error message is a string with a maximum length of 120 characters. Both error code and error message are required fields.

This object represents multiple tracking numbers. It includes properties for the sequence number, shipment key, and tracking number. The tracking number must be 18 characters long, start with "1Z," and consist of uppercase letters and numbers.

info.title: UPS Track Alert API
info.description:
# Product Info The UPS Track Alert API provides best in-class package tracking visibility with near real time event updates for an improved customer experience and stream line logistic management. Updates are pushed to the user as soon as available with no constant polling required, thereby improving operational efficiency. For more information on the UPS Track Alert API, please visit the Product Info page.

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

# Business Values - **Enhanced Customer Experience**: Near real-time tracking information increases transparency, leading to higher customer satisfaction and trust. - **Operational Efficiency**: Eliminates the necessity for continuous polling, thus saving resources and improving system responsiveness. - **Data-Driven Decision Making**: Access to near real-time data can help businesses optimize their supply chain and make informed logistics decisions. - **Optimizing Cash Flow Through Near Real-Time Delivery Tracking**: Improve cash flow by knowing that deliveries occurred in near real time. - **Mitigating Fraud and Theft through Near Real-Time Package Status Monitoring**: Reduce fraud and theft by knowing any time something happens to your packages. # How does it work once I am setup as a user? You submit up to 100 UPS 1Z package tracking numbers to the API at a time, using OAUTH in a JSON format. Your submission needs to include the URL where Track Alert will send a message with any events that occur to your 1Z package for the next 14 days. This saves you the effort of polling UPS to determine what is the current status of your package. # FAQs - **How do I check if a subscription to a 1Z was successful?** > Within 8 seconds of submitting a 1Z package tracking number to Track Alert, you will receive a message confirming successful and un-successful 1Z's. - **I stopped receiving event messages after 2 weeks and my package hasn’t been delivered. Why?** > Each 1Z subscription is valid for 14 days. If the package has not been delivered within 14 days, you must resubscribe to the 1Z to continue receiving updates/events. - **How do I get events that occurred prior to subscription?** > Track Alert does not retain any history. You should use the UPS Track API to receive history about your package. - **How many 1Z tracking numbers can a subscriber subscribe to in one request?** > You can subscribe to up to 100 1Z in each submission to the API. A reply message will be sent via the API with details showing successful and unsuccessful 1Z's submissions. - **What types of event data does Track Alert provide?** > In addition to the expected local dates and times when the event occurred (including GMT date and time), you will receive details about the event that include status-type, status-code, status-description and status-description code. Status types are: M and MV = manifest information, X = exception information (something out of the normal happened to your package, but it may still be delivered on time), I = in-progress (on the way or moving normally through the UPS network), U = update (there is an update to your package, normally the scheduled delivery has been updated, but it may still be delivered on time) D = delivery information (loaded on delivery vehicle, out for delivery, delivered) Status codes are a 2-character code that provide details about the event. There is a list of these codes and their translations elsewhere on this portal. Status descriptions are a very brief (a few words) describing the status code. Status-description code is a overly simplified description of the event. This description is intended for those who do not understand transportation. - **What does the message look like?** > This is what a message looks like for an event that is sent to your URL. Not every field will have a value for every message. We have converted the JSON format message to text format for clarity. Those fields are: 1Z package tracking number scheduled delivery date (this field maybe updated, example '20240905') actual delivery date (this field is blank until the delivery event occurs) actual delivery time (this field is blank until the delivery event occurs) activity location city activity location state/province activity location postal code (this field is blank until the delivery event occurs) activity location country activity status type activity status code activity status description activity status description code local activity date local activity time GMT activity date GMT activity time delivery start time (example '150000') delivery end time (example '170000') delivery time description (example 'estimated delivery window' or 'end of day') delivery photo (this field is only available for enhanced users) - **Can I test this process?** > Yes, there are two test 1Z's that you can submit, and resubmit that will send several events spaced 1 second apart. Those two test 1Z's are 1ZCIETST0111111114 and 1ZCIETST0422222228. Please ensure to use UPS Production CIE(https://wwwcie.ups.com/api/track/{version}). You can submit these 1Z's as often as you like. (no stress testing please.) # Error Codes | Error Code | HTTP Status | Description | |------------|-------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------| | VSS000 | 400 | Invalid request and The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS002 | 400 | Missing transId. | | VSS003 | 400 | Please enter a valid Transaction ID, The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS004 | 400 | Missing transactionSrc. | | VSS006 | 400 | Please enter a valid Transaction SRC, The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS100 | 500 | We're sorry, the system is temporarily unavailable. Please try again later. | | VSS110 | 400 | Subscription request is empty or not present. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS200 | 400 | Tracking Number List is required. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS210 | 400 | The Subscription request should have at least one valid tracking number. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS215 | 400 | The 1Z tracking number that was submitted is not a valid CIE 1Z and has been rejected. | | VSS220 | 400 | You have submitted over 100 1Z numbers which is not allowed. The entire submission of 1Z numbers has been rejected. Please resubmit your request again using groups of no more than 100 1Z numbers. | | VSS300 | 400 | Locale is required. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS310 | 400 | Please enter a valid locale. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS400 | 400 | Please enter a valid country code. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS500 | 400 | Destination is required. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS600 | 400 | URL is empty or not present. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS610 | 400 | URL is too long. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS700 | 400 | Credential is empty or not present. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS800 | 400 | CredentialType is empty or not present. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS930 | 400 | Type is missing or invalid, The Subscription request has been rejected.

flattened_text: The UPS Track Alert API provides real-time package tracking updates to enhance customer experience and streamline logistics. Users receive updates without constant polling, improving operational efficiency. Key benefits include enhanced customer satisfaction, operational savings, and data-driven decision-making. Users can submit up to 100 tracking numbers at a time and receive event updates for 14 days. The API provides status information such as delivery updates and exceptions. Error codes are provided for troubleshooting.

info.title: Export Assure API - Cross-Border Trade Guidance-v1
info.description:
This API offers businesses a powerful tool to manage shipping compliance with Description Guidance, Power of Attorney (POA) Requirements, UPS Prohibited Goods, and Commodity Compliance Guidance in order to help prevent delays, avoid fines, and keep your customers happy with fast, hassle-free customs clearances. For more information on the Export Assure API, please visit the Product Info page.

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

## Key Features ### 1. Basic Description Guidance (Free Feature) This feature helps you avoid commonly used, invalid shipment descriptions to avoid hold-ups at customs. For comprehensive description guidance, please refer the Interactive Commodity Description API. Basic Description Guidance includes: - Checking your commodity description against commonly used descriptions that typically result in a customs delay. - Provide basic guidance for improving an invalid commodity description. ### 2. Power of Attorney (POA) Requirements Understanding legal permissions is key for obeying international trade laws. This feature: - Reviews commodity details for POA requirements. - Determines when a POA is needed for customs clearance. - Proactively notifies user of POA requirement to help avoid customs delays. ### 3. UPS Prohibited Goods Guidance (Free Feature) Note that this must be turned on in order to use feature 4, - Reviews commodity details for POA requirements. - Note 1: evaluateImportExportRequirements is the name of the endpoint which performs the UPS Prohibited goods check. There is no charge to call this endpoint. - Note 2: evaluateImportExportRequirements MUST be set to true in order to use Feature #4 ### 4. Commodity Compliance Guidance (Premium Feature) This premium feature checks for any restrictions or prohibitions for the specific commodity you are shipping (including any forms needed to clear customs) for the country you are shipping to. A chargeable event is when guidance is provided, including that no restrictions and prohibitions are found. Commodity Compliance Guidance requires a full, destination country specific tariff code to provide guidance. If you do not have this for each product in each country you ship to, you can use the Export Assure: Interactive Commodity Description API to determine this. Included in Commodity Compliance Guidance is: - Details on what commodities can be shipped to and from specific locations, including restrictions based on the country of origin of the good. - Information specific to the commodities and origins/destinations. - Notification for international shipping forms needed for the commodity to clear customs. - Note 1: evaluateImportExportRequirements - the free feature for UPS Prohibited Goods - MUST be set to true in order to use Commodity Compliance Guidance - Note 2: advancedImportExportRequirements is the endpoint for Commodity Compliance Guidance, and will incur a charge each time guidance is provided

flattened_text: The Export Assure API provides tools for businesses to manage shipping compliance efficiently. It helps prevent delays, fines, and ensures smooth customs clearances. Key features include Basic Description Guidance, Power of Attorney (POA) Requirements, UPS Prohibited Goods Guidance, and Commodity Compliance Guidance. The API offers both free and premium features to assist with international trade laws, commodity restrictions, and necessary customs forms. For more details, visit the Product Info page and explore sample requests using Postman and GitHub.

This OpenAPI specification defines two server endpoints for UPS brokerage APIs: Production CIE - External Interface and Production - External Interface. Both endpoints support versioning with a default version of v1.

post.summary: Submit shipment details for compliance guidance

parameters.description: version

post.description:
Submit shipment details and receive guidance from UPS. 

This endpoint includes four separate operations which may be requested individually or simultaneously:
  -	Basic Description Guidance (Free Feature)
  -	Power of Attorney (POA) Requirements (Free Feature)
  -	UPS Prohibited Goods Guidance (Free Feature)
  -	Commodity Compliance Guidance (Premium Feature)
  -	NOTE: requires UPS Prohibited Goods Guidance (evaluateImportExportRequirements) to be set to true. 

  To request a specific operation, set the respective value for that property to true:
    -	evaluateDescriptions to request basic description guidance for the shipment (free)
  	- evaluatePoaRequirements to request POA requirements for the shipment (free)
    - evaluateImportExportRequirements to request UPS Prohibited Goods Guidance only (free)
    - evaluateAdvancedImportExportRequirements to request regulatory requirements, shipping restrictions, and required international forms (premium)
  Examples:
    -	To request only Description Guidance, set evaluateDescriptions: true and provide relevant description properties.
    -	To request all three free operations, set evaluateDescriptions: true, evaluatePoaRequirements: true, evaluateImportExportRequirements: true, and include all required properties for all operations.
    -	To request Commodity Compliance Guidance, set advancedImportExportRequirements: true, evaluateImportExportRequirements: true, and include all required properties for all operations.
    -	If you do not wish to be charged, set advancedImportExportRequirements: false

Each operation has specific properties to set for requesting. Examples are provided for different request scenarios. The endpoint requires certain parameters and returns responses based on the request status. It is secured using OAuth2 and falls under the Export Assure category.

To obtain these credentials, go to your app info page, select "Try It," enter your Client ID and Secret in the Security section, and request a token. Once you have the token, you can send your API requests using it. The authentication method used is client_secret_basic.

ComplianceDetails.description: This object contains details of specific compliance requirements and controls that are applicable to the shipment, based on whether it is for import or export purposes.

flattened_text: The ComplianceDetails object provides specific details about compliance requirements and controls for shipments, distinguishing between import and export purposes. It includes properties for category type (import or export) and control types. Both category type and control types are required fields.

ControlDetails.description: This object contains an array of warning messages related to this control type.

controlDetailName.description:
The formal name or title of the control measure. This property serves as the header for `ControlDetails`.  Where no specific control name is applicable, this field may be left empty (and consequently, no header will be displayed in the response). This property is translated to the user's language as required. 

**Note**: When the `controlTypeCode` is set to `DOC`, the `controlDetailName` is also the identifier for the corresponding DocuSign template.

controlDetailDescription.description: A detailed description of the control measure, translated for the user as required.
examples: Trade Agreement between the United States and Canada (USMCA)

flattened_text: The `ControlDetails` object contains information about a control measure, including a detailed description and a formal name or title. The description provides warning messages related to the control type. The `controlDetailName` serves as the header for `ControlDetails` and can also be used as an identifier for a DocuSign template when the `controlTypeCode` is set to `DOC`. The `controlDetailDescription` provides a detailed description of the control measure. Both properties are required and have specific character limits.

ControlTypes.description: This object includes specific type of customs controls applicable to a shipment.

controlType.description: The category of customs control applicable to the shipment. This property is translated to the user's language as required.

controlTypeCode.description: A unique code that distinctly identifies each control type. This code is not translated and is used for specific system-logic related to the control type.

isRequired.description: Whether shipment compliance with a specific control type is required

controlTypeMessage.description: Additional guidance or instructions based on the specific control type condition.
examples: Free Trade Agreement may be applicable

controlDetails.description: An array that contains a list of control types and codes

flattened_text: The `ControlTypes` object defines different types of customs controls for a shipment. It includes details like control type, code, message, and whether compliance is required. The `controlDetails` property lists control types and codes. `controlType` specifies the category of control, `controlTypeCode` provides a unique identifier, and `controlTypeMessage` gives additional guidance. The `isRequired` property indicates if compliance is necessary. The object is required to have `controlType`, `controlTypeCode`, `controlTypeMessage`, and `controlDetails` properties.

CountryCodes.description: The two-letter identification code for countries.

flattened_text: This field represents the two-letter identification codes for countries. Valid examples include AU, US, UK, FR, and JP. The code must be exactly 2 characters long and can only contain letters and numbers.

CurrencyCodes.description:
The three-letter code that represents the currency used to value the items in the shipment. | Supported enum values | | :--------------------------- | | `ARS`
Argentine Peso | | `AUD`
Australian Dollar | | `BRL`

It includes information on whether a keyword from the shipment description was matched, the matched keyword(s), a message for improving the description, and a list of terminology from a specific regional source.

ErrorResponse.description: This object is the primary container for error responses.

flattened_text: The ErrorResponse object is used to handle error responses. It contains performance statistics and a response wrapper. Both the response and performance statistics are required fields within this object.

ErrorResponseWrapper.description: This object contains an array of error codes.

flattened_text: The ErrorResponseWrapper object includes an array of error codes. It is required to have the 'errors' property, which is an array of ErrorCode objects.

flattened_text: This object defines error codes, descriptions, and related properties. It includes fields for the error code, description, field causing the error, additional message for the user, specific error type, and the value that triggered the error. The error code, description, field, message, type, and value are all strings with specific patterns and examples. The type field specifies the operation the error message relates to, with supported values like Description Guidance, Power of Attorney Requirement, and Import Export Compliance.

EvaluationCriteria.description:
Criteria for evaluating POA requirements for both importer and exporter. Supported values: | Supported enum values | | :-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | | `NonConditional`
Standard evaluation without specific conditional criteria | | `Description`
Evaluation based on the detailed description of the commodity | | `FTA`
Free Trade Agreement. Evaluation considers Free Trade Agreement stipulations applicable to the shipment. | | `Value`
Evaluation based on the monetary value of the commodities | | `HTS`
Harmonized Tariff Schedule. Evaluation uses HTS codes for tariff classification and compliance | | `Quantity`
Evaluation focuses on the quantity of the goods being shipped | | `Weight`
Evaluation based on the weight of the shipment |

flattened_text: The `EvaluationCriteria` defines different criteria for evaluating requirements for both importers and exporters. The supported values include `NonConditional` for standard evaluation, `Description` based on commodity details, `FTA` considering Free Trade Agreement stipulations, `Value` based on monetary value, `HTS` using HTS codes for classification, `Quantity` focusing on goods quantity, and `Weight` based on shipment weight. The criteria must be between 3 and 14 characters long and can only contain letters, numbers, spaces, colons, hyphens, and underscores.

ExportAssureRequest.description: This object is the primary request structure for the Export Assure API.

transID.description: The unique, reference identifier that correlates an API request with its response

evaluateDescriptions.description: Whether the user has requested description guidance

evaluatePoaRequirements.description: Whether the user has requested Power of Attorney (POA) requirements

evaluateAdvancedImportExportRequirements.description: Whether the user has requested an Advanced Import/Export Compliance review

evaluateImportExportRequirements.description: Whether the user has requested an Import/Export Compliance review

flattened_text: The ExportAssureRequest object is used as the main request structure for the Export Assure API. It includes properties to indicate if the user has requested various compliance reviews and guidance. It also contains a unique transaction ID and a reference to a ShipmentRequest object. The transaction ID is a string with a maximum length of 50 characters and can contain any characters. The shipment property is required in every request.

ExportAssureResponse.description: This object is the primary request container for the Export Assure API.

flattened_text: The ExportAssureResponse object is used as the main container for the Export Assure API requests. It includes performance statistics, shipment details, and a transaction ID. All three properties are required.

ExportAssurePartialResponse.description: This object is the primary response container for the Export Assure API.

flattened_text: The `ExportAssurePartialResponse` object is the main response for the Export Assure API. It includes performance statistics, error response details, shipment information, and a transaction ID. All properties are required.

HsCode.description: The [Harmonized System (HS) code](https://www.trade.gov/harmonized-system-hs-codes). Used commonly throughout the export process for goods, the Harmonized System is a standardized numerical method of classifying traded products. It is used by customs authorities to identify products when assessing duties and taxes.

flattened_text: The HsCode field represents the Harmonized System (HS) code, a standardized numerical classification system used in the export process for goods. Customs authorities use this code to identify products and determine duties and taxes. The field allows for a string input with a maximum length of 13 characters, following a specific numeric pattern. Examples of HS codes include 3605.00.00.00 and 3925.90.00.00.

ImportExportShipmentLevelResponse.description: This object contains properties which describe the shipment's compliance with laws and regulations.

shipmentValue.description: The total monetary value of all items included in the shipment

shipmentCurrencyCode.description: The three-letter code of the currency used to value the items in the shipment.

hasShipmentWarnings.description: Whether there are shipment-level warning. Shipment-level warnings include issues related to documentation and shipment packaging.

hasCommodityWarnings.description: Whether there are compliance-related warnings or issues at the commodity level within the shipment. A `true` value indicates potential compliance concerns that require the shipper's attention.

commodityWarningsMessage.description: The warning message returned when the `hasCommodityWarnings` flag is set to true
examples: Your shipment may have additional clearance considerations
Some shipment items may be prohibited from import to the EU

isShipmentOverGiftValueThreshold.description: Whether the total value of the shipment exceeds the allowable threshold for categorizing it as a gift

shipmentOverGiftValueThresholdMessage.description: The message returned if the shipment's value surpasses the threshold for gift categorization
examples: Your shipment may not be considered as a gift by Customs authorities due to the shipment value provided
Your shipment may incur additional charges due to shipment value.

isShipmentOverGiftWeightThreshold.description: Whether the total weight of the shipment exceeds the weight limit for being classified as a gift

shipmentOverGiftWeightThresholdMessage.description: A message explaining the implications if the shipment's weight goes beyond the threshold for gift categorization, guiding users in understanding customs considerations.
examples: Your shipment may not be considered as a gift by Customs authorities due to the shipment weight provided
Your shipment may incur additional charges due to shipment weight.

flattened_text: The `ImportExportShipmentLevelResponse` object describes a shipment's compliance with laws and regulations. It includes properties like warning messages for compliance issues, flags indicating warnings at commodity and shipment levels, and thresholds for gift categorization based on value and weight. Other properties include shipment currency code, messages for exceeding gift thresholds, shipment value, and translation locale. The object is required to have specific properties and is structured as an object type.

ImportExportItemLevelResponse.description: This object includes details of the Import Export Compliance assessment.

isUpsProhibited.description: Whether UPS prohibits shipment of the item

upsProhibitedMessage.description: A message explaining the reason for any prohibited shipment
examples: US federal law prohibits shipment of this item from the US.
The EU prohibits import of this item.

isTranslatedIndicator.description: Whether shipment details have been translated from the language of the origin country to the user's language

complianceOutput.description: This array includes the output of the compliance review, including customs category and control codes.

flattened_text: The `ImportExportItemLevelResponse` object provides details of the Import Export Compliance assessment. It includes information such as the output of the compliance review, whether the shipment details have been translated, whether UPS prohibits shipment of the item, and a message explaining any prohibited shipment. The object has required fields for indicating if UPS prohibits shipment and if the details have been translated.

PowerOfAttorneyResponse.description: This object includes details of the Power of Attorney (POA) requirements for the shipment.

importerPoaRequiredFlag.description: Whether Power of Attorney (POA) is required for the importer

importerPoaOnFileIndicator.description: Whether the importer already has a POA on file

importerCommodityId.description: The first commodity in the shipment that necessitates an importer POA

importerCommodityDescription.description: A description of the commodity regarding what led to the POA requirement for the importer

exporterPoaRequiredFlag.description: Whether the exporter is required to provide a POA for customs clearance.

exporterEvaluationCriteria.description: This schema includes details of whether a POA is required for the exporter.

exporterPoaOnFileIndicator.description: Whether the exporter has a POA already on file

exporterCommodityId.description: The first commodity in the shipment that necessitated an exporter POA

exporterCommodityDescription.description: The commodity that triggers the POA requirement for the exporter

exporterOnlineFormFlag.description: Whether there is an online form available for the exporter to complete their POA documentation

exporterDocuSignTemplateId.description: The ID of the DocuSign template, which the exporter can use for electronic completion of the POA.

flattened_text: The PowerOfAttorneyResponse object provides details about Power of Attorney (POA) requirements for a shipment. It includes information such as the commodity triggering the POA requirement for the exporter, DocuSign template ID for electronic completion of POA, evaluation criteria, and flags indicating if POA is required for the exporter and importer. The object specifies whether an online form is available for the exporter and importer, and if they already have a POA on file.

ShipmentRequest.description: This object contains all necessary details about a shipment for compliance evaluation.

info.title: OAuth Client Credentials API
info.description:
The UPS OAuth Client Credentials API helps retrieve an OAuth Bearer token when the integration owner is also the UPS shipper. The integration owner uses their UPS login credentials, and the UPS account number, to receive a token that can be used in the authorization HTTP header of subsequent API calls to UPS APIs like the Ship API, Track API, etc. - Client Credentials - Accelerate API Integration with UPS SDKs

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

flattened_text: The UPS OAuth Client Credentials API allows integration owners who are also UPS shippers to obtain an OAuth Bearer token. By using their UPS login credentials and account number, integration owners can get a token for authorization in subsequent API calls to UPS services like Ship API and Track API. Explore the API documentation and sample applications on GitHub. You can also try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman.

servers.description: Customer Integration Environment for Client Credentials

parameters.name: x-merchant-id
parameters.description: 6-digit UPS account number.

flattened_text: This endpoint `/security/v1/oauth/token` allows clients to create a token using OAuth client credentials. The request requires a 6-digit UPS account number in the header. The request body must include a `grant_type` parameter with the value `client_credentials`. Responses include success, invalid request, unauthorized request, blocked merchant, and quota limit exceeded. Basic authentication is required. Two server URLs are provided for different environments.

BasicAuth.description:
Find your Client ID and Secret on your app info page.
1. Select \"Try It\"
2. In the Security section enter your Client ID as the Username and your Secret as the Password.
3. Enter any additional information in the Body and Parameters sections.
4. Select \"Send\" to execute your API request

flattened_text: To access the API, use Basic Authentication with your Client ID as the Username and Secret as the Password. Find these credentials on your app info page. Enter them in the Security section, along with any other required information, and send your request to execute the API call.

access_token.description: Token to be used in API requests.

expires_in.description: Expire time for requested token in seconds.

refresh_count.description: Number of refreshes for requested token.

flattened_text: This response object provides details about a successfully generated token for API requests. It includes the access token, client ID, expiration time, issue time, refresh count, scope, status, and token type.
This defines a token error response object that includes a reference to the error response schema.
This defines a wrapper for error responses that includes an array of error items. Each error item follows the schema defined in the "errors" component.
This section defines the structure of error responses. Each error includes a code (string) and a message (string).

info.title: Guaranteed Quote API v1
info.description:
This API provides a Global Landed Cost (GLC) duty and tax rate quote for shippers. ## Key Business Values - Simplifies the International Cross Border shipping process. For more information on the Global Checkout API, please visit the Product Info page. Appendix

Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

flattened_text: This API, called the Guaranteed Quote API v1, provides duty and tax rate quotes for shippers to simplify international shipping. For more information, visit the Product Info and Appendix pages on the UPS developer website. Explore API documentation and sample applications on GitHub.
This OpenAPI document defines two server URLs for UPS services: one for the Customer Integration Environment and one for Production. Both URLs include a version variable set to 'v1'.

post.summary: returns a guaranteed landed cost quote
post.description: This endpoint requests guaranteed quotes for landed cost duties and taxes.

errors.message: The token was invalid/expired or could not be verified

flattened_text: This endpoint allows you to request guaranteed quotes for landed cost duties and taxes. You can provide details about the shipment, including items, addresses, and costs. After submitting the request, you will receive a response with the total cost breakdown and quote details. The endpoint requires OAuth2 authentication.

OAuth2.description:
"Find your Client ID and Secret on your app info page.
1. Select \\\"Try It\\\"
2. In the Security section enter your Client ID and Secret.
3. Select \\\"Request Token\\\"
4. Enter any additional information in the Body and Parameters sections.
5. Select \\\"Send\\\" to execute your API request"

flattened_text:
The API documentation includes two security schemes: JWTAuth and OAuth2. 

- JWTAuth uses a bearer token with the format JWT.
- OAuth2 requires obtaining a Client ID and Secret from the app info page. The OAuth2 flow involves entering the Client ID and Secret, requesting a token, providing additional information, and sending the API request.

It requires information such as the buyer's currency code, a reference number for tracking, the UPS service level code, details of the shipment, the shipper's UPS account number, and the shipper's currency code. The buyer's currency code and shipper's currency code must adhere to the ISO 4217 standard. The service level code corresponds to different UPS service options.

flattened_text: This API defines a shipment request with details like export and import country codes, ship date, addresses, shipment items, and transport information. It includes fields for specifying insurance costs, shipment type, transportation modes, and transport costs. Certain fields have specific formats and constraints. The request must include import and export country codes, shipper and ship-to addresses, and shipment items. It includes fields for item description, dimensions (height, length, width), gross weight, origin country code, part number, quantity, and unit price. The dimensions and weight have units of measure specified. The quantity includes the count and unit of measure. The `unitPrice` field references charge details.

The quote ID, creation timestamp, expiration date, and global checkout total are required fields.

Each field has a description, example value, and character limits. The postal code field has specific examples, length constraints, and a pattern for validation. The addressLine1 and countryCode fields are required.

info.title: Landed Cost Quote API
info.description:
The Landed Cost Quote API allows you to estimate the all-inclusive cost of international shipments - including applicable duties, VAT, taxes, brokerage fees, and other fees. Required parameters include the currency and shipment details, such as the commodity ID, price, quantity, and country code of origin. Key Business Values: - **Enhanced Customer Experience**: Get a quick and accurate quote on the landed cost of a shipment, including the cost of goods, transportation, and any other fees associated with getting the goods to their destination. - **Operational Efficiency**: Simplify the process of calculating landed costs by eliminating the need to manually research and calculate all of the different fees involved. - **Data-Driven Decision Making**: Improve decision-making by having a clear understanding of the total cost of shipping goods before you commit to a purchase.. - **Optimizing Cash Flow**: Streamline your shipping process by integrating the Landed Cost Quote API into your existing systems. # Reference - Business Rules - Appendix - Errors

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

flattened_text: The Landed Cost Quote API helps estimate the total cost of international shipments, including duties, taxes, and fees. It requires currency and shipment details like commodity ID, price, quantity, and origin country code. Benefits include improved customer experience, operational efficiency, data-driven decisions, and optimized cash flow. For more information, refer to the Business Rules, Appendix, and Errors sections. Explore the API using Postman and sample applications on GitHub.
This OpenAPI specification defines two server URLs: one for the Customer Integration Environment at "https://wwwcie.ups.com/api" and one for Production at "https://onlinetools.ups.com/api".

currencyCode.description: Specifies the currency of transaction or purchase.

allowPartialLandedCostResult.description:
An optional flag to indicate that partial landed cost calculations are acceptable to be used by upstream systems.
When set to *false*, the system will return an error when at least one commodity in the shipment is invalid (all or none), and no results  will be sent back for that request. When set to *true*, the system will return partial calculations when applicable.

Valid values: true = Partial Landed Cost result will return. false = All or No result will return (default).

alversion.description: Version number of the instance that processed this request. This must match the major number of the corresponding ICD version.

LandedCostRequest.description: The root element for the Landed Cost document.

flattened_text: The LandedCostRequest is the main element in the Landed Cost document. It includes information like whether partial landed cost calculations are allowed, the version number, currency code, shipment details, and a unique transaction ID. The request must include the currency code, transaction ID, version number, and shipment information.

LandedCostRequest_Shipment.description: Every Landed Cost request must be based on a shipment.

id.description: Specifies the Shipment ID in the Landed Cost quote. It is an arbitrary string provided by the user of the API and will be  returned with the Landed Cost Quote to indicate which shipment the tariffs apply to. There are similar IDs associated with the Product and Order objects.

importCountryCode.description: Specifies the Import/Ship-To/Destination/Final country of the shipment. Please check country list in the Appendix.

importProvince.description: Province/State is supported only for a few countries such as Mexico, Canada, etc. Please check Province list in the Appendix

shipDate.description: Defaults to current date if not provided. Date format: YYYY-MM-DD.

incoterms.description:
Supported Incoterm Values:
1. CFR - Cost & Freight 
2. CIF - Cost, Insurance & Freight 
3. CIP - Carriage and Insurance Paid-To 
4. CPT - Carriage Paid-To 
5. DAP - Delivered At Place 
6. DAT - Delivered At Terminal 
7. DDP - Delivered Duty Paid 
8. DPU - Delivered at Place Unloaded 
9. EXW - Ex Works 
10. FAS - Free Alongside Ship 
11. FCA - Free Carrier 
12. FOB - Free On Board (Default)

exportCountryCode.description:
Specifies the export/ship-from/origin country of the shipment. Please check country List in the Appendix section.

**Note:** Export country code must be different from the import country code.

transModes.description:
The modes of transportation (in upper case).
Supported Values: 
1. INT_AIR 2. 
INT_OCEAN 
3. INT_RAIL 
4. INT_TRUCK 
5. DOM_AIR 
6. DOM_OCEAN 
7. DOM_RAIL 
8. DOM_TRUCK 

Default value will vary based on the import country.

transportCost.description:
Specifies the Freight charge or transport costs, which are used for tariff calculations. Landed cost result might have some dependency on the freight charges in some countries. Therefore, freight amount should be always provided for accurate Landed Cost result. 

Allowed values:
 1. Any non-negative floating-point number. 
2. Numeric value with optional decimal value.

shipmentType.description:
Specifies the shipment type such as Gift, Document, Commercial (Sale), etc.

Supported Shipment Types: 
1. GIFT 
2. COMMERCIAL 
3. SALE 
4. SAMPLE 
5. REPAIR 
6. RETURN 
7. OTHER 

Default value will vary and based on import country.

shipmentItems.description: Array of shipment item objects (commodities), that are in a shipment.

flattened_text: This section defines the structure of a Landed Cost request based on a shipment. It includes details such as the export and import country codes, shipment ID, incoterms, ship date, shipment items, shipment type, transportation modes, and transport costs. Some fields have specific format requirements and default values. The request must include a unique shipment ID, import and export country codes, and shipment items.

commodityId.description: Commodity ID is used to associate tariffs with product in the output. Should be unique for each commodity in a request. It is an arbitrary string provided by the user of the API that will be returned with the Landed Cost Quote to indicate which commodity the tariffs apply to.

grossWeight.description: Specifies the gross weight of the commodity as any non-negative value.

grossWeightUnit.description: Specifies the units of the gross weight. Required if GrossWeight is used. If GrossWeight is not specified, this value must not be set to anything but null. Supported values: LB, KG

priceEach.description: Specifies the price for each commodity unit in the settlement currency. The total price of the entire number of shipmentItems may not exceed 999999999999.99

commodityCurrencyCode.description: Specifies the Currency Code used for commodity price. All commodities must have the same currency code.

quantity.description: Specifies the number of product units to be shipped. The total price of the entire number of shipmentItems may not exceed 999999999999.99, 1 or greater than 1

UOM.description: Specifies unit of measure. Check UOM List in the Appendices section.

hsCode.description: Specifies a valid HS or HTS code for the shipment's destination or import country. This field is required if description is not provided.

description.description: This field is populated with description of the commodity. This field is required if hsCode is not provided.

flattened_text: This API endpoint is used to request shipment items. It includes properties such as unit of measure, commodity currency code, commodity ID, description, gross weight, gross weight unit, HS code, origin country code, price each, and quantity. Some fields are required, like commodity ID, price each, commodity currency code, quantity, unit of measure, and origin country code. The data types include strings, numbers, and integers, with specific constraints on lengths and values.

shipment.description: Every Landed Cost response must be based on a shipment.

currencyCode.description: Specifies the Currency Code set at the commodity level. This currency is applicable for all duty, tax, VAT, and fee at the shipment and commodity level.

importCountryCode.description: Specifies the Import/Ship-To/Destination/Final country of the shipment. Please check country list in the Appendices section.

totalShipmentLevelTaxesAndFees.description: Total tax and other fees at shipment level.

totalDutyAndTax.description: Grand total of the combined duty, VAT, tax, and other fees of all commodities in this shipment including shipment level taxes and fees.

shipmentItems.description: An array of Landed Cost for all valid commodities.

transID.description: An identifier unique to the request.

absLayerTime.description: Time taken through the abstraction layer in milliseconds.

It includes details like shipment ID, currency code, total costs, and performance statistics. The response must have information about the shipment, version number, and a unique identifier. It also provides data on brokerage fees, taxes, and fees at both commodity and shipment levels. The response structure is defined with required fields and maximum limits for certain properties.

chargeName.description:
Brokerage charge name for this shipment. Possible Values:
1. Entry Preparation Fee 
2. Disbursement Fee 
3. Additional Line Fee

chargeAmount.description: Fee amount for the brokerage charges.

flattened_text: This section defines brokerage fee items with two properties: charge amount and charge name. The charge amount is a number representing the fee amount, while the charge name is a string specifying the type of brokerage charge for the shipment. The charge name has a maximum length of 50 characters and can be one of three predefined values: Entry Preparation Fee, Disbursement Fee, or Additional Line Fee.

hsCode.description: Specifies the HTS code of the commodity.

totalCommodityTaxAndFee.description: Total tax and other fees for this commodity (excluding commodity duty and VAT).

commodityCurrencyCode.description: Specifies the currency code used for commodity's price.

isCalculable.description: True/False. Indicates if Landed Cost can successful calculated for this commodity.

flattened_text: This response provides information about shipment items, including details like commodity ID, duty amount, VAT amount, HTS code, and more. It specifies the currency code, duty, VAT, and tax for each commodity. It also indicates if the landed cost can be successfully calculated for each item. Certain fields like commodity ID, HTS code, duty, VAT, and others are required.

info.title: Interactive Description Guidance
info.description:
The Interactive Commodity Description API will guide an International shipper through a series of multiple-choice questions in order to improve the commodity description such that it can be tied to a full, destination country specific Harmonized Tariff Schedule code (HTS). The tariff code is used for expediting customs clearance, avoiding customs holds, and ensuring accurate assessing of duties and taxes. Both an updated, natural language description and tariff code will be returned. The chargeable event is the return of the full tariff code. For more information on the Interactive Description API, please visit the Product Info page.

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

flattened_text: The Interactive Commodity Description API helps international shippers provide accurate commodity descriptions by answering multiple-choice questions. This ensures the description aligns with the destination country's Harmonized Tariff Schedule code, expediting customs clearance and avoiding delays. The API returns both the updated description and tariff code. For more information, visit the Product Info page. Explore UPS APIs and sample requests using Postman and GitHub.

This OpenAPI specification defines two server URLs for UPS API. One is for the Customer Integration Environment with a base URL of https://wwwcie.ups.com/api/export-assure/{version}, and the other is for the Production environment with a base URL of https://onlinetools.ups.com/api/export-assure/{version}. Both URLs use the default version v1.

Initiates an interactive description session for a product. Users can start a session by sending a POST request to /interactive. The request must include a 128-bit GUID in the header as "transId," the user or application name as "transactionSrc," and the API version in the path. The API requires OAuth2 security and is categorized under the "Interactive Description" tag.

post.summary: Continues refinement of product description and HTS code via questions and answers.
post.description:
This endpoint facilitates the ongoing interactive process for refining a product description and determining its corresponding Harmonized Tariff Schedule (HTS) code. 

After initiating a session with the initial product description using the /interactive endpoint, users can continue their interaction via this endpoint by providing answers to the questions returned from the previous interaction. Each interaction refines the product description further, helping the system to accurately identify the correct HTS code. The {sessionId} parameter uniquely identifies the user's session and ensures that the interaction is continued seamlessly.

id.description:
The "id" field in the response structure represents the unique identifier of the question that was answered.
This identifier helps track which specific question the user's response corresponds to, ensuring the accuracy and continuity of the interactive session. It is used to maintain the sequence of interactions and to provide context for subsequent questions and answers.

selected.description:
The "selected" field represents the index of the chosen option from the multiple-choice answers provided for a specific question. 
This is a 0-based index, meaning the first option is represented by 0, the second by 1, and so on.
This field ensures that the system accurately records the user's choice and continues the interactive session based on the selected answer.

flattened_text: The "Answer" object contains two fields: "id" and "selected." The "id" field stores the unique identifier of the answered question to track user responses accurately. The "selected" field indicates the index of the chosen option from multiple-choice answers, starting from 0. These fields ensure the system records user choices correctly and maintains the interactive session flow.

id.description: The id field represents the unique identifier of the specific question for which the user is submitting feedback. This identifier ensures that the feedback is accurately associated with the correct question within the session.

sentiment.description: The "sentiment" field is a boolean that indicates the user's sentiment towards the specific question. A value of true represents a positive sentiment, while a value of false represents negative sentiment.

feedback.description: An optional field for user input to describe the reason for their sentiment.

assumed.description: Identifies whether the API selected an answer to the corresponding question without having to explicitly ask it to the user. The value true means that the answer was assumed by the API, while false means that the answer was selected by the user.

flattened_text:
The "History" object in the API response includes three properties: "assumed," "id," and "selected." 

- "assumed" indicates whether the API assumed the answer or the user selected it.
- "id" is the unique identifier of the question answered, helping track the user's responses.
- "selected" is the index of the chosen option in multiple-choice answers, ensuring accurate recording of user choices. 

These properties are required in the response object to maintain the interaction sequence and context.

newProductDescription.description: An enhanced description generated for the product after processing product details.

actualHts.description: The Harmonized Tariff Schedule (HTS) code representing the currently provided "newProductDescription"

suggestedHts.description: The API's prediction for what the final Harmonized Tariff Schedule (HTS) code might be based on the current point of the session.

confidence.description: A value between 0.00 and 1.00 representing the APIs likeliness for a suggestedHts to be the final HTS code. A value of 1.00 can also be interpreted as 100% confidence.

noMoreQuestions.description: This field will be marked as true when the API doesn't have any more questions to ask the user. In this case, the questions list will be empty and the most complete "actualHts" is provided.

flattened_text: The `InteractiveResponse` object contains information generated by an API for product classification. It includes the Harmonized Tariff Schedule (HTS) code for the product, a confidence score indicating the accuracy of the suggested HTS code, an enhanced product description, a flag indicating if there are more questions to ask, a list of questions, session details, and the API's predicted HTS code. The `newProductDescription` and `session` fields are required.
This API endpoint, IterateRequest, requires an array of questions to be provided in the request. Each question should follow the schema defined in the Answer component.

For all intensive purposes, selecting an option from the other list should be treated as an indexable list as a continuation of options. For example, if "options" is a list of 5 items, selecting the first value from "other" would be index 5.

info.title: DeliveryDefense API
info.description:
Address Confidence For more information on the Delivery Defense API, please visit the Product Info page.

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

# Purpose The API is designed to enable customers to obtain an Address Confidence score based on analysis of historical data.

info.title: UPS Track Alert API with Photo
info.description:
# Product Info The UPS Track Alert API provides best in-class package tracking visibility with near real time event updates for an improved customer experience and stream line logistic management. Updates are pushed to the user as soon as available with no constant polling required, thereby improving operational efficiency. For more information on the UPS Track Alert API with Photo, please visit the Product Info page.

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

# Business Values - **Enhanced Customer Experience**: Near real-time tracking information increases transparency, leading to higher customer satisfaction and trust. - **Operational Efficiency**: Eliminates the necessity for continuous polling, thus saving resources and improving system responsiveness. - **Data-Driven Decision Making**: Access to near real-time data can help businesses optimize their supply chain and make informed logistics decisions. - **Optimizing Cash Flow Through Near Real-Time Delivery Tracking**: Improve cash flow by knowing that deliveries occurred in near real time. - **Mitigating Fraud and Theft through Near Real-Time Package Status Monitoring**: Reduce fraud and theft by knowing any time something happens to your packages. # How does it work once I am setup as a user? You submit up to 100 UPS 1Z package tracking numbers to the API at a time, using OAUTH in a JSON format. Your submission needs to include the URL where Track Alert will send a message with any events that occur to your 1Z package for the next 14 days. This saves you the effort of polling UPS to determine what is the current status of your package. # FAQs - **When can I expect a delivery photo?** > Delivery photos are only available with residential deliveries in package release areas. Additional message with the delivery photo will be sent, if and when the photo is made available. - **How do I check if a subscription to a 1Z was successful?** > Once 1Z package tracking number(s) is submitted to Track Alert, you will receive a response confirming successful and unsuccessful 1Z's. - **I stopped receiving event messages after 2 weeks and my package hasn’t been delivered. Why?** > Each 1Z subscription is valid for 14 days If the package has not been delivered within 14 days, you must resubscribe to the 1Z to continue receiving updates/events. - **How do I get events that occurred prior to subscription?** > Track Alert does not retain any history. You should use the UPS Track API to receive history about your package. - **How many 1Z tracking numbers can a subscriber subscribe to in one request?** > You can subscribe to up to 100 1Z in each submission to the API. A reply message will be sent via the API with details showing successful and unsuccessful 1Z's submissions. - **What types of event data does Track Alert provide?** > In addition to the expected local dates and times when the event occurred (including GMT date and time), you will receive details about the event that include status-type, status-code, status-description and status-description code. Status types are: M and MV = manifest information, X = exception information (something out of the normal happened to your package, but it may still be delivered on time), I = in-progress (on the way or moving normally through the UPS network), U = update (there is an update to your package, normally the scheduled delivery has been updated, but it may still be delivered on time) D = delivery information (loaded on delivery vehicle, out for delivery, delivered) Status codes are a 2-character code that provide details about the event. There is a list of these codes and their translations elsewhere on this portal. Status descriptions are a very brief (a few words) describing the status code. Status-description code is a overly simplified description of the event. This description is intended for those who do not understand transportation. - **What does the message look like?** > This is what a message looks like for an event that is sent to your URL. Not every field will have a value for every message. We have converted the JSON format message to text format for clarity. Those fields are: 1Z package tracking number scheduled delivery date (this field maybe updated, example '20240905') actual delivery date (this field is blank until the delivery event occurs) actual delivery time (this field is blank until the delivery event occurs) activity location city activity location state/province activity location postal code (this field is blank until the delivery event occurs) activity location country activity status type activity status code activity status description activity status description code local activity date local activity time GMT activity date GMT activity time delivery start time (example '150000') delivery end time (example '170000') delivery time description (example 'estimated delivery window' or 'end of day') delivery photo (this field is only available for enhanced users) - **Can I test this process?** > Yes, there are two test 1Z's that you can submit, and resubmit that will send several events spaced 1 second apart. Those two test 1Z's are 1ZCIETST0111111114 and 1ZCIETST0422222228. Please ensure to use UPS Production CIE(https://wwwcie.ups.com/api/track/{version}). You can submit these 1Z's as often as you like. (no stress testing please.) # Error Codes | Error Code | HTTP Status |Description | |------------|-------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------| | VSS000 | 400 | Invalid request and The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS002 | 400 | Missing transId. | | VSS003 | 400 | Please enter a valid Transaction ID, The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS004 | 400 | Missing transactionSrc. | | VSS006 | 400 | Please enter a valid Transaction SRC, The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS100 | 500 | We're sorry, the system is temporarily unavailable. Please try again later. | | VSS110 | 400 | Subscription request is empty or not present. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS200 | 400 | Tracking Number List is required. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS210 | 400 | The Subscription request should have at least one valid tracking number. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS215 | 400 | The 1Z tracking number that was submitted is not a valid CIE 1Z and has been rejected. | | VSS220 | 400 | You have submitted over 100 1Z numbers which is not allowed. The entire submission of 1Z numbers has been rejected. Please resubmit your request again using groups of no more than 100 1Z numbers. | | VSS300 | 400 | Locale is required. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS310 | 400 | Please enter a valid locale. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS400 | 400 | Please enter a valid country code. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS500 | 400 | Destination is required. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS600 | 400 | URL is empty or not present. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS610 | 400 | URL is too long. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS700 | 400 | Credential is empty or not present. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS800 | 400 | CredentialType is empty or not present. The Subscription request has been rejected. | | VSS930 | 400 | Type is missing or invalid, The Subscription request has been rejected.

flattened_text: The UPS Track Alert API with Photo provides real-time package tracking updates to enhance customer experience and streamline logistics. Users receive updates without constant polling, improving operational efficiency. Key benefits include enhanced customer experience, operational efficiency, data-driven decision-making, and cash flow optimization. Users can submit up to 100 tracking numbers at a time and receive event updates for 14 days. The API offers FAQs, error code information, and test options for users.

info.title: Time In Transit
info.description:
The Time In Transit API provides estimated delivery times for various UPS shipping services, between specified locations. Key Business Values: - **Enhanced Customer Experience**: Allows businesses provide accurate delivery estimates to their customers, enhancing customer service. - **Operational Efficiency**: Helps in logistics planning by providing transit times for different UPS services. # Reference - Appendix - Errors

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

flattened_text: The Time In Transit API provides estimated delivery times for different UPS shipping services between specified locations. This API helps businesses offer accurate delivery estimates to customers, improving customer service. It also aids in logistics planning by providing transit times for various UPS services. You can explore the API documentation and sample applications on GitHub and try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman.
This OpenAPI specification defines two server URLs: one for the Customer Integration Environment at https://wwwcie.ups.com/api and one for Production at https://onlinetools.ups.com/api.
