ShipperExportDeclarationIndicator.description: The empty tag in request indicates that customer would be using UPS prepared SED form.  Valid for UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments.

CommercialInvoiceRemovalIndicator.description: Presence/Absence Indicator. Any value inside is ignored. CommercialInvoiceRemovalIndicator - empty tag means indicator is present. CommercialInvoiceRemovalIndicator allows a shipper to dictate that UPS remove the Commercial Invoice from the user's shipment before the shipment is delivered to the ultimate consignee.

SDLShipmentIndicator.description: Empty Tag means the indicator is present. This field is a flag to indicate if the receiver needs SDL rates in response. True if SDLShipmentIndicator tag exists; false otherwise.  If present, the State Department License (SDL) rates will be returned in the response.This service requires that the account number is enabled for SDL.

EPRAIndicator.description:
For valid values, refer to Rating and Shipping COD Supported Countries or Territories in the Appendix.Presence/Absence Indicator. Any value inside is ignored. This field is a flag to indicate Package Release Code is requested for shipment.

This accessorial is only valid with ShipmentIndicationType '01' - Hold for Pickup at UPS Access Point™.

InsideDelivery.description:
Inside Delivery accessory. Valid values:
- 01 - White Glove
- 02 - Room of Choice
- 03 - Installation  Shippers account needs to have a valid contract for Heavy Goods Service.

ItemDisposalIndicator.description: Presence/Absence Indicator. Any value inside is ignored. If present, indicates that the customer would like items disposed.   Shippers account needs to have a valid contract for Heavy Goods Service.

Shipment_ShipmentServiceOptions.description: Shipment level Accessorials are included in this container.

flattened_text: This container holds various options for a shipment, such as delivery preferences and special services. Each property represents a different aspect of the shipment, like Saturday delivery or document return. These options help customize the shipping process based on specific requirements or restrictions.

CurrencyCode.description: Access Point COD Currency Code.  Required if Access Point COD container is present. UPS does not support all international currency codes. Refer to the appendix for a list of valid codes.

MonetaryValue.description:
Access Point COD Monetary Value.  Required if Access Point COD container is present.

8 digits prior to the decimal place and 2 after.

ShipmentServiceOptions_AccessPointCOD.description:
Access Point COD indicates Shipment level Access Point COD is requested for a shipment.  Valid only for "01 - Hold For Pickup At UPS Access Point" Shipment Indication type.

Shipment Access Point COD is valid only for countries or territories within E.U.

Not valid with (Shipment) COD.

Not available to shipment with return service.

flattened_text: The `ShipmentServiceOptions_AccessPointCOD` object is used to request Access Point COD (cash on delivery) for a shipment. This feature is only available for shipments held for pickup at UPS Access Points within the European Union. It cannot be used with regular COD or for shipments with return service. The object includes properties for the currency code and monetary value required for Access Point COD. The currency code must be 3 characters long, and the monetary value must have 8 digits before the decimal and 2 after.

CODFundsCode.description: For valid values, refer to Rating and Shipping COD Supported Countries or Territories in the Appendix.

ShipmentServiceOptions_COD.description: If present, indicates C.O.D. is requested for the shipment.  Shipment level C.O.D. is only available for EU origin countries or territories.C.O.D. shipments are only available for Shippers with Daily Pickup and Drop Shipping accounts.

flattened_text: This service option, ShipmentServiceOptions_COD, indicates if Cash on Delivery (C.O.D.) is requested for the shipment. C.O.D. is only available for EU origin countries or territories and for shippers with Daily Pickup and Drop Shipping accounts. The properties include CODAmount and CODFundsCode, with specific requirements for CODFundsCode values.

CurrencyCode.description: COD amount currency code type.

MonetaryValue.description: COD Amount.

ShipmentServiceOptions_COD_CODAmount.description: CODAmount Container.  UPS does not support all international currency codes. Refer to the appendix for a list of valid codes.

flattened_text: This component defines the COD (Cash on Delivery) amount for a shipment. It includes the currency code and the monetary value. The currency code must be a 3-character string, and the monetary value must be an 8-character string. Both fields are required. UPS supports specific international currency codes, which can be found in the provided list.

DCISType.description: Type of delivery confirmation.  Valid values: 1 - Delivery Confirmation Signature Required 2 - Delivery Confirmation Adult Signature Required

ShipmentServiceOptions_DeliveryConfirmat.description: Delivery Confirmation Container.  DeliveryConfirmation and C.O.D. are mutually exclusive. Refer to the Appendix for a list of valid origin-destination country or territory pairs associated with each confirmation type.

flattened_text: This section defines the Delivery Confirmation options for shipments. You can choose between two types of confirmation: Delivery Confirmation Signature Required (Type 1) or Delivery Confirmation Adult Signature Required (Type 2). Note that Delivery Confirmation and C.O.D. options cannot be used together. Only one Delivery Confirmation option can be selected.

LiftGateAtPickupIndicator.description: The presence of the tag LiftGatePickupRequiredIndicator indicates that the shipment requires a lift gate for pickup.

HoldForPickupIndicator.description: The presence of the tag HoldForPickupIndicator indicates that the user opted to hold the shipment at UPS location for pickup.

ShipmentServiceOptions_PickupOptions.description: Shipment Service Pickup Options Container.  Valid for UPS Worldwide Express Freight and UPS Worldwide Express Freight Midday shipments.

flattened_text: The `ShipmentServiceOptions_PickupOptions` object contains options for UPS Worldwide Express Freight and UPS Worldwide Express Freight Midday shipments. It includes properties like `HoldForPickupIndicator` for holding the shipment at a UPS location and `LiftGateAtPickupIndicator` for shipments requiring a lift gate at pickup.

LiftGateAtDeliveryIndicator.description: The presence of the tag LiftGateAtDeliveryIndicator indicates that the shipment requires a lift gate for delivery.

DropOffAtUPSFacilityIndicator.description: The presence of the tag DropOffAtUPSFacilityIndicator indicates the package will be dropped at a UPS facility for shipment.

ShipmentServiceOptions_DeliveryOptions.description: Shipment Service Delivery Options Container.  Valid for UPS Worldwide Express Freight and UPS Worldwide Express Freight Midday shipments.

flattened_text: This section defines delivery options for UPS Worldwide Express Freight services. It includes options for dropping off packages at a UPS facility and requiring a lift gate for delivery. The maximum number of options allowed is 1.

AlcoholicBeveragesIndicator.description: This field is a flag to indicate if the package has Alcohol. True if present; false otherwise.  Valid for UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments.

DiagnosticSpecimensIndicator.description: This field is a flag to indicate if the package has Biological substances. True if present; false otherwise.  Valid for UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments. Lane check will happen based on postal code/ city.

PerishablesIndicator.description: This field is a flag to indicate if the package has Perishables. True if present; false otherwise.  Valid for UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments.

PlantsIndicator.description: This field is a flag to indicate if the package has Plants. True if present; false otherwise.  Valid for UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments.

SeedsIndicator.description: This field is a flag to indicate if the package has Seeds. True if present; false otherwise.  Valid for UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments.

SpecialExceptionsIndicator.description: This field is a flag to indicate if the package has Special Exceptions Restricted Materials. True if present; false otherwise.  Valid for UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments.

TobaccoIndicator.description: This field is a flag to indicate if the package has Tobacco. True if present; false otherwise.  Valid for UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments.

ECigarettesIndicator.description: This field is a flag to indicate if the package has E-Cigarettes. True if present; false otherwise.  Valid for UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments.

HempCBDIndicator.description: This field is a flag to indicate if the package has Hemp/CBD. True if present; false otherwise.  Valid for UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments.

ShipmentServiceOptions_RestrictedArticle.description: Restricted Articles container.  Valid for UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments.

flattened_text: This container defines various indicators for restricted articles in UPS World Wide Express Freight shipments. It includes flags for items like alcoholic beverages, diagnostic specimens, e-cigarettes, hemp/CBD, perishables, plants, seeds, special exceptions, and tobacco. Each indicator is a boolean value (true or false) to specify the presence of the corresponding item in the package. Lane checks may occur based on postal code or city.

Code.description: Code for type of Import Control shipment. Valid values are: '01' = ImportControl Print and Mail '02' = ImportControl One-Attempt                                     '03' = ImportControl Three-Attempt'04' = ImportControl Electronic Label '05' = ImportControl Print Label.

Description.description: Text description of the code representing the Import Control associated with the shipment.

ShipmentServiceOptions_ImportControl.description: Container for type of Import Control shipments.

flattened_text: This section defines the ShipmentServiceOptions_ImportControl object, which is used to specify the type of Import Control shipments. It includes properties for the shipment code and a text description. The code must be 2 characters long and can have values like '01' for ImportControl Print and Mail. The description can be up to 50 characters long. The Code property is required.

Code.description: Code for type of Return shipment. Valid values are:'2' = UPS Print and Mail Return Label '3' =UPS One-Attempt Return Label'5' = UPS Three Attempt Return Label'8' = UPS Electronic Return Label'9' = UPS Print Return Label'10' = UPS Exchange Print Return Label                            '11' = UPS Pack & Collect Service 1-Attempt Box 1 '12' = UPS Pack & Collect Service 1-Attempt Box 2 '13' = UPS Pack & Collect Service 1-Attempt Box 3 '14' = UPS Pack & Collect Service 1-Attempt Box 4 '15' = UPS Pack & Collect Service 1-Attempt Box 5 '16' = UPS Pack & Collect Service 3-Attempt Box 1 '17' = UPS Pack & Collect Service 3-Attempt Box 2 '18' = UPS Pack & Collect Service 3-Attempt Box 3 '19' = UPS Pack & Collect Service 3-Attempt Box 4 '20' = UPS Pack & Collect Service 3-Attempt Box 5  10 = UPS Exchange Print Return Label and 5 = UPS Three Attempt Return Label are not valid for UPS WorldWide Express Freight and UPS Worldwide Express Freight Midday Services. 3 = UPS One-Attempt Return Label is not valid return service with UPS Premium Care accessorial.

Description.description: Description for type of Return Service.

ShipmentServiceOptions_ReturnService.description: Container for type of Return Services.

flattened_text: This section defines the options for return services related to shipments. It includes a code to specify the type of return service and a description of the service. The code values range from '2' for UPS Print and Mail Return Label to '20' for various UPS Pack & Collect services. Some codes have restrictions based on the UPS service type. The description field provides a brief explanation of the return service. The code is required, and the description is optional.

NegotiatedRatesIndicator.description: NegotiatedRatesIndicator -  Required to display two types of discounts: 1) Bids or Account Based Rates2) Web/Promotional Discounts BidsAccount Based Rates: If the indicator is present, the Shipper is authorized, and the Rating API XML Request is configured to return Negotiated Rates, then Negotiated Rates should be returned in the response. Web/Promotional Discounts: If the indicator is present, the Shipper is authorized for Web/Promotional Discounts then Negotiated Rates should be returned in the response.

FRSShipmentIndicator.description: FRS Indicator. The indicator is required to obtain rates for UPS Ground Freight Pricing (GFP).  The account number must be enabled for GFP.

RateChartIndicator.description: RateChartIndicator -  If present in a request, the response will contain a RateChart element.

UserLevelDiscountIndicator.description: UserLevelDiscountIndicator - required to obtain rates for User Level Promotions.  This is required to obtain User Level Discounts. There must also be no ShipperNumber in the Shipper container.

TPFCNegotiatedRatesIndicator.description: This indicator applies for a third party (3P) / Freight collect (FC) shipment only. For 3P/FC shipment if the shipper wishes to request for the negotiated rates of the third party then this indicator should be included in the request. If authorized the 3P/FC negotiated rates will be applied to the shipment and rates will be returned in response.

flattened_text: The `Shipment_ShipmentRatingOptions` object contains various indicators for obtaining specific shipping rates and discounts. These indicators include FRS Indicator for UPS Ground Freight Pricing, Negotiated Rates Indicator for displaying discounts, RateChart Indicator for including a RateChart element in the response, TPFC Negotiated Rates Indicator for third party shipments, and UserLevelDiscount Indicator for User Level Promotions. Each indicator has specific requirements and impacts on the rate calculation and response.

CurrencyCode.description: Invoice Line Total Currency type. The Currency code should match the origin country's or territory's currency code, otherwise the currency code entered will be ignored.  Note: UPS doesn't support all international currency codes. Please check the developer guides for Supported Currency codes.

MonetaryValue.description: Total amount of the invoice accompanying the shipment. Required when the InvoiceLineTotal container exists in the rate request.  Valid values are from 1 to 99999999.

Shipment_InvoiceLineTotal.description: Container to hold InvoiceLineTotal Information.  Required if the shipment is from US/PR Outbound to non US/PR destination with the PackagingType of UPS PAK(04).Required for international shipments when using request option "ratetimeintransit" or "shoptimeintransit".

flattened_text: This container, Shipment_InvoiceLineTotal, holds information about the total invoice amount for a shipment. It is required for outbound shipments from the US/PR to non-US/PR destinations using UPS PAK packaging type. It is also needed for international shipments when using specific request options. The container includes CurrencyCode (currency type) and MonetaryValue (total invoice amount). CurrencyCode must match the origin country's currency code. MonetaryValue should be between 1 and 99999999.

PromoCode.description: Promotion Code. A discount that is applied to the user.  Required if PromotionalDiscountInformation container is present.

PromoAliasCode.description: Promotion Alias code  Required if PromotionalDiscountInformation container is present.

Shipment_PromotionalDiscountInformation.description: PromotionalDiscountInformation container. This container contains discount information that the customer wants to request each time while placing a shipment.

flattened_text: This object, `Shipment_PromotionalDiscountInformation`, contains discount information that customers can request when placing a shipment. It includes properties for a Promotion Alias code and a Promotion Code, both required when using this container. The maximum occurrences for this container is 1.

PackageBillType.description:
Valid values are:
- 02 - Document only
- 03 - Non-Document
- 04 - WWEF Pallet
- 07 - Domestic Pallet

If 04 is included, Worldwide Express Freight and UPS Worldwide Express Freight Midday services (if applicable) will be included in the response.

Shipment_DeliveryTimeInformation.description: Container for requesting Time In Transit Information. Required to view time in transit information.  Required to view any time in transit information.

flattened_text: This object, "Shipment_DeliveryTimeInformation," is used to request Time In Transit Information. It includes properties such as PackageBillType, Pickup, and ReturnContractServices. The PackageBillType property specifies the type of shipment (e.g., Document only, Non-Document). The object is required to view any time in transit information and can only have one instance.

Date.description: Shipment Date; The Pickup date is a Shipment Date and it is a required input field.  The user is allowed to query up to 35 days into the past and 60 days into the future. Format: YYYYMMDD  If a date is not provided, it will be defaulted to the current system date.

Time.description: Reflects the time the package is tendered to UPS for shipping (can be dropped off at UPS or picked up by UPS).  Military Time Format HHMMSS or HHMM.   Invalid pickup time will not be validated.

flattened_text: This section defines the information needed for scheduling a pickup. It includes the shipment date and time for when the package will be picked up by UPS. The date must be in YYYYMMDD format and can be up to 35 days in the past or 60 days in the future. The time must be in military time format (HHMMSS or HHMM). The pickup date is required, and if not provided, it defaults to the current date.

Code.description: Return contract Service code. Valid Code "01" - Heavy Goods. If 01 will return Heavy Goods service transit times for a given origin and destination (if applicable)  Invalid Code will be ignore.

Description.description: Return contract service Description

flattened_text: This endpoint provides information about return contract services. It includes a service code (e.g., "01" for Heavy Goods) and a description of the service. The code must be 2 characters long and the description must be between 1 and 35 characters. The code is required for this object.

RatedShipment.description:
RatedShipment Container.

**NOTE:** For versions >= v2409, this element will always be returned as an array. For requests using versions < v2409, this element will be returned as an array if there is more than one object and a single object if there is only 1.

flattened_text: The RateResponse object contains information about shipping rates. It includes a RatedShipment container that may be returned as an array depending on the API version used. The object also includes a Response container. Both RatedShipment and Response are required properties of the RateResponse object.

Alert.description:
Alert Container.  There can be zero to many alert containers with code and description.

**NOTE:** For versions >= v2403, this element will always be returned as an array. For requests using versions < v2403, this element will be returned as an array if there is more than one object and a single object if there is only 1.

AlertDetail.description:
Alert Detail Container. Currently applies to and returned only for request containing HazMat and SubVersion greater than or equal to 1701.

**NOTE:** For versions >= v2403, this element will always be returned as an array. For requests using versions < v2403, this element will be returned as an array if there is more than one object and a single object if there is only 1.

flattened_text: The `RateResponse_Response` object is a response container that includes various properties such as `Alert`, `AlertDetail`, `ResponseStatus`, and `TransactionReference`. The `Alert` property contains alert containers with code and description. For versions greater than or equal to v2403, this element will always be returned as an array. The `AlertDetail` property contains alert detail containers and is only applicable for requests with HazMat and SubVersion greater than or equal to 1701. Similar to `Alert`, for versions >= v2403, this element will always be returned as an array. The `ResponseStatus` and `TransactionReference` properties are references to other schemas. The `ResponseStatus` property is required, and the object is named `Response` in XML.

Code.description: Identifies the success or failure of the transaction.   1 = Successful

Description.description: Describes Response Status Code.  Returns text of "Success" for a valid request.

flattened_text: This section defines the structure of a response status container. It includes two properties: "Code" indicates the success or failure of the transaction, with "1" representing success, and "Description" provides a text description, typically "Success" for valid requests. Both properties are required and the container is represented as an object named "ResponseStatus" in XML.

Code.description: Warning code returned by the system.

Description.description: Warning messages returned by the system.

Response_Alert.description: Alert container. There can be zero to many alert containers with code and description.

flattened_text: This defines an "Alert" object that can contain warning code and messages from the system. The warning code is a string with a maximum length of 10 characters, and the message has a maximum length of 150 characters. Both the code and message are required fields in the object.

Code.description: Warning code returned by the system.

Description.description: Warning messages returned by the system.

flattened_text: This response object, "AlertDetail," includes a warning code and message returned by the system. It also references additional element-level information. The "Code" and "Description" properties are required, with specific length constraints. The object is in XML format and represents detailed alerts.

Level.description:
Define type of element in request. Possible values are -
- 'H' for the header details level,
- 'S' for the shipment level,
- 'P' for the package level,
- 'C' for the commodity level.

ElementIdentifier.description:
Contains more information about the type of element. Returned if Level is 'P' or 'C'.

**NOTE:** For versions >= v2403, this element will always be returned as an array. For requests using versions < v2403, this element will be returned as an array if there is more than one object and a single object if there is only 1.

AlertDetail_ElementLevelInformation.description: Provides more information about the element that represents the alert.

flattened_text: This element provides additional details about the alert being represented. It includes the ElementIdentifier, which gives more information about the type of element. The Level property defines the type of element in the request, such as header details, shipment, package, or commodity. The ElementIdentifier will always be returned as an array for versions >= v2403. The Level property is required and can only have a single character value.

Code.description: Represents the type of element. Possible values are 'P' and 'C'.

Value.description: Represents the value of element.

flattened_text: This data structure defines an element with an identifier consisting of a code and a value. The code can be either 'P' or 'C', while the value can be up to 5 characters long. The value and code are required fields.

CustomerContext.description: The CustomerContext Information which will be echoed during response.

flattened_text: This defines a response object called "TransactionReference" that contains CustomerContext information. The CustomerContext field can be up to 512 characters long and will be included in the response.

Disclaimer.description:
Disclaimer is used to provide more information to the shipper regarding the processed shipment. It is used to notify the shipper about possible taxes and duties that might have been added or might apply to the shipment. Refer to the Appendix for various disclaimers. Rate Type with which Shipment is rated. Possible RateChart values for different regions will be:

US 48 origin:
- 1 – Daily Rates
- 3 – Standard List Rates
- 4 – Retail Rates.

Alaska/Hawaii origin:
- 1 – Daily Rates
- 3 – Standard List Rates
- 4 – Retail Rates.

All Other origins:
- 1 – Rates
- 5 - Regional Rates
- 6 - General List Rates.
- 3 and 4 do not apply

flattened_text: This component defines the structure of a Rate Response for a shipment. Some elements are returned as arrays based on the version used. Certain fields are only included if specific indicators are present in the request. The response object must include billing weight, total charges, service options charges, service, transportation charges, and rated package.

Code.description: Code representing type of Disclaimer. Refer to the Appendix for possible code values.

When using a negotiated divisor different from the published UPS divisor (139 for inches and 5,000 for cm), the weight returned is based on the published divisor. Rates, however, are based on the negotiated divisor.

Some properties are specific to international shipments, such as delay count and holiday count. The object is required to have values for DayOfWeek, Pickup, Arrival, and BusinessDaysInTransit.

info.title: OAuth Authorization Code API
info.description:
The UPS OAuth Authorization Code API helps integrate UPS services into your business application for providing the service your application grants your customers. For example, you can create UPS shipping labels with shipping rates for merchants from within your application. Since your application will not have access to your customer's UPS login credentials, the OAuth authorization code flow is used to let your customer use their UPS credentials, within your application, in a simple and secure way. The PKCE-enhanced Authorization Code Flow introduces a secret created by the calling application that can be verified by the authorization server; this secret is called the Code Verifier. Additionally, the calling app creates a transform value of the Code Verifier called the Code Challenge and sends this value over HTTPS to retrieve an Authorization Code. This way, a malicious attacker can only intercept the Authorization Code, and they cannot exchange it for a token without the Code Verifier. Key Business Values: - **Enhanced Transaction Security**: The OAuth Authorization Code flow is more secure and reliable since the access token and the refresh token are never exposed in the browser's URL, thus reducing the risk of leakage or theft. - **Operational Efficiency**: With the ability to obtain a refresh token when the token expires, your application can maintain a long-term and uninterrupted access to the protected resources, without requiring the user to re-authenticate or re-login. Overview of steps in OAuth Authorization Code flow: 1. When user selects Login, the client application redirects to the authorization server's /authorize endpoint. 2. The Authorization Server authenticates the user by asking for their login credentials, and after successful login, the authorization server responds back to the application with an authorization code contained within a redirection URI. 3. The application then sends the authorization code and the redirection URI to the authorization server's /oauth/token endpoint. 4. The authorization server's /token endpoint verifies the authorization code and the application's client ID contained in the redirect URI, and responds with a with an access token, as well as a refresh token. 5. The Client application uses the access token to request information from an UPS API. Overview of steps in OAuth Authorization Code PKCE flow: 1. When user selects Login, the client application redirects to the authorization server's /authorize endpoint with Code Challenge - **Note:** Prior to redirecting to the authorization server, the application generates and **code_challenge** and **code_verifier** that are related in this way: code_challenge = BASE64URL-ENCODE(SHA256(ASCII(code_verifier))) 2. The Authorization Server authenticates the user by asking for their login credentials, and after successful login, the authorization server responds back to the application with an authorization code contained within a redirection URI. 4. The application then sends the authorization code , code_verifer and the redirection URI to the authorization server's /oauth/token endpoint. - **Note:** When utlizing the PKCE flow, the BASIC Authorization header should **not** be included, just the **client_id** parameter in the body. 5. The authorization server's /token endpoint verifies the authorization code, code_verifier and the application's client ID contained in the redirect URI, and responds with a with an access token, as well as a refresh token. 6. The Client application uses the access token to request information from an UPS API. - Setting-up OAuth Authorization Code flow - Accelerate API Integration with UPS SDKs

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

flattened_text: The UPS OAuth Authorization Code API allows your business application to integrate UPS services, such as creating shipping labels and rates, for your customers. It uses OAuth authorization code flow for secure access without exposing customer credentials. The PKCE-enhanced flow adds an extra layer of security with a Code Verifier. Benefits include enhanced security and operational efficiency. The process involves steps like redirecting to the authorization server, obtaining access tokens, and refreshing tokens. For detailed setup and SDK integration, refer to the provided links. Explore UPS APIs with example requests using Postman and access documentation on GitHub.

get.description: The Authorize Client endpoint initiates the OAuth Authorization Code flow by redirecting the user to UPS for logging-in and authorize the client application. To begin the authorization flow, the application constructs a URL using the application's client Id, the redirect URI, the scope of permissions requested, and a random string used for subsequent verification. A successful response redirects back to the client with an authorization code that can be exchanged for an access token.

parameters.name: client_id
parameters.description: The public identifier for your application, obtained when you, the developer first registered the application.

parameters.name: redirect_uri
parameters.description: URL that tells the authorization server where to send the user back to after they approve the request.

parameters.name: response_type
parameters.description: Valid Values: code

parameters.name: state
parameters.description: A random string generated by the application and included in the request to prevent CSRF attacks. The application checks that the same value is returned after the user authorizes the app.

parameters.name: scope
parameters.description: One or more space-separated strings indicating which permissions the application is requesting.

parameters.name: code_challenge
parameters.description: Base64 URL-Encoded SHA256 value of Code Verifier that can be used to verify the code_verifier in the /token step.

location.description:
The UPS login redirection URI in the following format: https://www.ups.com/lasso/signin?client_id={client_id}&redirect_uri={redirect_uri}&response_type=code&scope={scope}&state={state}&type=ups_com_api

The value of 'state' will be the same value that the application initially set in the request.
The 'code' is the authorization code generated by the authorization server.

appname.description: Name of the application requesting the authorization code.

displayname.description: Display name of the application requesting the Authorization code.

flattened_text: The `/v1/oauth/authorize` endpoint initiates the OAuth Authorization Code flow. It redirects users to log in and authorize the client application. The application constructs a URL with client ID, redirect URI, requested permissions, and a random string for verification. A successful response returns an authorization code for an access token. The endpoint requires parameters like client ID, redirect URI, response type, and optional parameters like state and scope. The response includes headers with application and display names, and a redirection URI for UPS login. Possible responses include success, invalid request, unauthorized request, blocked merchant, and rate limit exceeded. Servers are available for customer integration and production environments.

post.description: The Generate Token endpoint exchanges the authorization code received from the client application for an access token and a refresh token. The client uses the access token to make API requests on behalf of the user by including it in the authorization header. The access token will expire after a certain period and can be refreshed by using the /refresh endpoint.

code.description: Authorization code from the UPS login system.

redirect_uri.description: Callback URL for the requesting application.

code_verifier.description: **Only required for PKCE flow**. A randomly generated secret created by the calling application that can be verified by the authorization server.

client_id.description: **Only required for PKCE flow**. The public identifier for your application, obtained when you, the developer first registered the application.

flattened_text: The `/v1/oauth/token` endpoint allows a client application to exchange an authorization code for an access token and a refresh token. The access token is used to make API requests on behalf of the user. The endpoint requires parameters like client ID, authorization code, and redirect URI. Responses include success, invalid request, unauthorized request, blocked merchant, and rate limit exceeded. Security is enforced with Basic Authentication. This endpoint is part of the OAuth Auth Code category and is available in both Customer Integration and Production environments.

post.description: The /refresh endpoint is used to refresh an expired access token in order to continue accessing a UPS API on behalf of a user. The endpoint generates a new access/refresh token pair by exchanging a valid refresh token. A successful response returns new access and refresh tokens for ongoing API access without re-prompting the user.

flattened_text: The `/v1/oauth/refresh` endpoint is used to refresh an expired access token for continued access to a UPS API on behalf of a user. By exchanging a valid refresh token, this endpoint generates a new access/refresh token pair. A successful response provides new tokens without requiring user interaction. Various responses handle different scenarios like successful operation, invalid request, unauthorized request, blocked merchant, and rate limit exceeded. This endpoint requires Basic Authentication and is available in both Customer Integration and Production environments.

BasicAuthGenerate.description:
- **Flow 1: Plain Auth-Code**

Find your Client ID and Secret on your app info page. 
 1. Select \"Try It\"
 2. In the Security section enter your Client ID as the Username and your Secret as the Password.
 3. Enter any additional information in the Body and Parameters sections.
 4. Select \"Send\" to execute your API request

 - **Flow 2: Auth-Code with PKCE [no http Authorization header required]**
 1. Select \"Try It\"
 2. Include the **client_id** and **code_verifier** parameters in the body of the request. Do not include an Authorization header.
 3. Enter any additional information in the Body and Parameters sections.
 4. Select \"Send\" to execute your API request

BasicAuthRefresh.description:
Find your Client ID and Secret on your app info page. 
1. Select \"Try It\"
2. In the Security section enter your Client ID as the Username and your Secret as the Password.
3. Enter any additional information in the Body and Parameters sections.
4. Select \"Send\" to execute your API request

flattened_text:
The `BasicAuthGenerate` security scheme allows you to authenticate using either Plain Auth-Code or Auth-Code with PKCE. For Plain Auth-Code, use your Client ID and Secret in the Security section. For Auth-Code with PKCE, include `client_id` and `code_verifier` in the request body. No Authorization header is needed. Execute your API request by providing additional information and selecting "Send."

The `BasicAuthRefresh` security scheme also requires your Client ID and Secret for authentication. Enter these in the Security section, provide any additional information, and select "Send" to execute your API request.

refresh_token_expires_in.description: Expiration time for requested refresh token in seconds.

issued_at.description: Issue time of requested token in milliseconds.

access_token.description: Token to be used in API requests.

refresh_token.description: Refresh token to be used in refresh requests when obtaining new access token.

refresh_token_issued_at.description: Time that refresh token was issued in milliseconds.

expires_in.description: Expire time for requested token in seconds.

refresh_count.description: Number of refreshes for requested token.

flattened_text: This response provides detailed information about a generated token for API requests. It includes the access token, client ID, expiration time, issue time, refresh token details, scope, and status. The response also specifies the type of access token generated.

refresh_token_expires_in.description: Expiration time for requested refresh token in seconds.

issued_at.description: Issue time for requested token in milliseconds.

access_token.description: Token to be used in API requests.

refresh_token.description: Token to be used in refresh requests.

refresh_token_issued_at.description: Issue time for requested refresh token in milliseconds.

expires_in.description: Expiration time for requested access token in seconds.

refresh_count.description: Number of refreshes for requested token.

flattened_text: The `refreshTokenSuccessResponse` object contains various properties related to a successful refresh token request. These properties include the access token, client ID, expiration times for both access and refresh tokens, issue times, refresh count, token status, scope, and token type. Each property is a string type.

info.title: Address Validation - Street Level
info.description:
The Address Validation Street Level API can be used to. check addresses against the United States Postal Service database of valid addresses in the U.S. and Puerto Rico. # Reference - Appendix - Business Rules - Errors - FAQ

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

flattened_text: The Address Validation Street Level API helps verify addresses against the USPS database for valid addresses in the U.S. and Puerto Rico. You can access additional resources like appendices, business rules, errors, and FAQs. Explore UPS APIs with example requests using Postman and find sample applications on GitHub.
This OpenAPI specification defines two server URLs: one for the Customer Integration Environment at "https://wwwcie.ups.com/api" and one for Production at "https://onlinetools.ups.com/api".

post.description: The Address Validation Street Level API can be used to check addresses against the United States Postal Service database of valid addresses in the U.S. and Puerto Rico. NOTE: In the Customer Integration Environment, Street Level Address Validation will only produce results for addresses in New York (NY) and California (CA).

If True, either the region element or any  combination of Political Division 1,  Political Division 2, PostcodePrimaryLow and the PostcodeExtendedLow fields will  be recognized for validation in addition to  the urbanization element. If False or no  indicator, street level address validation  is provided

Valid values:
- 1 - Address Validation
- 2 - Address Classification
- 3 - Address Validation and Address Classification.

For a list of valid values, refer to Address Validation API Supported Countries or Territories in the Appendix.

Users can specify processing options and the number of candidates to return. The API supports address validation, classification, or both. The API version 'v2' is required. Users can provide a sample JSON request for testing. Responses include success, invalid request, unauthorized request, blocked merchant, and rate limit exceeded. The API requires OAuth2 security.

OAuth2 uses client credentials and the token URL is https://wwwcie.ups.com/security/v1/oauth/token. The authentication method is client_secret_basic.

This component, XAVRequestWrapper, is an object that wraps an XAVRequest. It can only contain one XAVRequest object. The XAVRequest property is required and must be included. The XML element representing this object is named XAVRequest.

The `XAVResponseWrapper` object contains a single property called `XAVResponse`, which refers to the `XAVResponse` schema. The `XAVResponse` property is required and the object is represented in XML as `XAVResponse`.

RegionalRequestIndicator.description: If this indicator is present then either the region element or any combination of Political Division 1, Political Division 2, PostcodePrimaryLow and the PostcodeExtendedLow fields will be recognized for validation in addition to the urbanization element.  If this tag is present, US and PR street level address validation will not occur. The default is to provide street level address validation.  Not valid with the address classification request option.

MaximumCandidateListSize.description:
The maximum number of Candidates to return for this request.

- Valid values: 0 - 50
- Default: 15

flattened_text: The `XAVRequest` object is used to configure an address validation request. It includes properties such as `AddressKeyFormat`, `MaximumCandidateListSize`, and `RegionalRequestIndicator`. The `MaximumCandidateListSize` property specifies the maximum number of candidates to return, with a default of 15 and a range of 0 to 50. The `RegionalRequestIndicator` property controls the validation behavior based on region elements. The object is required to have `AddressKeyFormat` and `Request` properties.

RequestOption.description:
Identifies the optional processing to be performed. If not present or invalid value then an error will be sent back.

Valid values:

- 1 - Address Validation
- 2 - Address Classification
- 3 - Address Validation and Address Classification.

For a list of valid values, refer to Address Validation API Supported Countries or Territories in the Appendix.

flattened_text: The `XAVRequest_Request` object is a container for an Address Validation request. It includes the `RequestOption` property to specify the type of processing to be done (such as Address Validation or Classification). The `SubVersion` property is not used. The `TransactionReference` property refers to another schema. The `RequestOption` property is required.

CustomerContext.description: The CustomerContext Information which will be echoed during response.

Request_TransactionReference.description: TransactionReference identifies transactions between client and server.

flattened_text: This object, Request_TransactionReference, is used to identify transactions between a client and server. It includes a property called CustomerContext, which contains information echoed in the response. The CustomerContext is a string with a maximum length of 512 characters.

ConsigneeName.description: Name of business, company or person. Ignored if user selects the RegionalRequestIndicator.

AttentionName.description: Name of the building. Ignored if user selects the RegionalRequestIndicator.

AddressLine.description: Address line (street number, street name and street type) used for street level information. Additional secondary information (apartment, suite, floor, etc.). Applicable to US and PR only. Ignored if user selects the RegionalRequestIndicator.

Region.description:
If this node is present the following tags will be ignored:

- Political Division 2
- Political Division 1
- PostcodePrimaryLow
- PostcodeExtendedLow

Valid only for US or PR origins only.  Using this tag for non US/PR origins may cause address format errors.

PostcodeExtendedLow.description: 4 digit Postal Code extension. For US use only.

Urbanization.description: Puerto Rico Political Division 3. Only Valid for Puerto Rico.

CountryCode.description: Country or Territory Code. For a list of valid values, refer to the Address Validation API Supported Countries or Territories table in the Appendix.

XAVRequest_AddressKeyFormat.description:
AddressKeyFormat container.
The Key format is based on addressing standards jointly developed by the Postal Service and mailing industry.  The information provided in the Address Key container will be returned in the same format.

flattened_text: The `XAVRequest_AddressKeyFormat` object defines the format for an address key used in the Address Validation API. It includes details like address line, recipient name, country code, state, city, and postal code. Some fields are specific to the US and Puerto Rico. The `Region` field can be used to override certain address components. The `CountryCode` field is mandatory.

ValidAddressIndicator.description: Indicates query found a valid match.

AmbiguousAddressIndicator.description: Indicates query could not find exact match. Candidate list follows.

Candidate.description:
Candidate Container.

**NOTE:** For versions >= v2, this element will always be returned as an array. For requests using version = v1, this element will be returned as an array if there is more than one object and a single object if there is only 1.

flattened_text: The `XAVResponse` object is a container for the response of an address validation query. It includes properties such as `AddressClassification`, `AmbiguousAddressIndicator`, `Candidate`, `NoCandidatesIndicator`, `Response`, and `ValidAddressIndicator`. The `Candidate` property may return as an array depending on the API version used. The `Response` property is required.

Alert.description:
Alert Container.  There can be zero to many alert containers with code and description.

**NOTE:** For versions >= v2, this element will always be returned as an array. For requests using version = v1, this element will be returned as an array if there is more than one object and a single object if there is only 1.

flattened_text: This response container includes an alert container that can have multiple alerts with codes and descriptions. For versions >= v2, alerts are always returned as an array. For version = v1, alerts are returned as an array if there are multiple objects and as a single object if there is only one. The response also includes status and transaction reference information. The response is required to have a status and is represented as an object in XML with the name "Response."

Code.description:
Identifies the success or failure of the transaction. Valid values:
1 = Success
0 = Failure

Description.description: Describes Response Status Code.  Returns text of 'Success' or 'Failure'.

flattened_text: This component defines the structure of a response status container. It includes two properties: "Code" indicates the success or failure of the transaction with values 1 for success and 0 for failure, and "Description" provides a text description of the status as either 'Success' or 'Failure'. The properties have specific length and type requirements.

Code.description: Warning code returned by the system.

Description.description: Warning messages returned by the system.

flattened_text: This response alert object includes a warning code and message returned by the system. The warning code is a string with a maximum length of 10 characters, while the warning message has a maximum length of 150 characters. Both the code and message are required fields. The object is named "Alert" in XML format.

CustomerContext.description: The CustomerContext Information which will be echoed during response.

flattened_text: This defines a response object called "TransactionReference" that contains CustomerContext information. The CustomerContext field can be up to 512 characters long and will be included in the response.

Code.description:
Contains the classification code of the input address.

Valid values:

- 0 - UnClassified
- 1 - Commercial
- 2 - Residential

Description.description: Contains the text description of the address classification code: UnClassified, Commercial, Residential

flattened_text: This data structure represents an address classification, with a code and description. The code can be 0 for Unclassified, 1 for Commercial, or 2 for Residential. The description provides a text description of the classification. The code is a single character, and the description is limited to 15 characters. Both the code and description are required fields in this object.

This defines a response object called XAVResponse_Candidate, which can have a maximum of 1 instance. It includes properties for AddressClassification and AddressKeyFormat, with AddressKeyFormat being required. The object is of type object and is represented in XML as Candidate.

Code.description:
Contains the classification code of the address:
0 - UnClassified
1 - Commercial
2 - Residential

It includes properties for Code (classification code) and Description (text description of the code). The Code property can have values 0 (UnClassified), 1 (Commercial), or 2 (Residential). The Description property has a maximum length of 15 characters. Both properties are required.

ConsigneeName.description: Name of business, company or person. Not returned if user selects the RegionalRequestIndicator.

AttentionName.description: Name of building. Not returned if user selects the RegionalRequestIndicator.

AddressLine.description: Address line (street number, street name and street type, and political division 1, political division 2 and postal code) used for street level information. Additional secondary information (apartment, suite, floor, etc.) Applicable to US and PR only.  Not returned if user selects the RegionalRequestIndicator.

Region.description: Single entry containing in this order  Political Division 2, Political Division 1 and Post Code Primary Low and/or PostcodeExtendedLow.

PoliticalDivision1.description: State/Province.  Returned if the location is within a State/Province/Territory. For International: returned if user enters valid Country or Territory Code, and City/postal code and it has a match.  For Domestic addresses, the value must be a valid 2-character value (per US Mail standards).  For International the full State or Province name will be returned.

PostcodeExtendedLow.description: Low-end extended postal code in a range. Example in quotes: Postal Code 30076-'1234'.  Only returned in candidate list. May be alphanumeric

Urbanization.description: Puerto Rico Political Division 3. Only Valid for Puerto Rico.

CountryCode.description: A country or territory code. Required to be returned.

The structure is organized as an object with various properties like "AddressLine," "AttentionName," "ConsigneeName," etc. Each property has specific character limits and conditions for when it is returned. info.title: Paperless Document
info.description:
The Paperless Documents API allows users to upload specific trade documents for paperless processing of international shipments.
The /upload endpoint of the API requires document details, including file name, file format, and document type (such as authorization form, commercial invoice, certificate of origin, export license, etc).
The /image endpoint helps users upload document images as support documents for shipping
The /delete endpoint of the API helps delete a specific document the user has uploaded. # Reference - Business Rules - Errors - FAQ

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

flattened_text: The Paperless Documents API enables users to upload trade documents for processing international shipments electronically. This component is a wrapper for a delete request for paperless documents. It contains a single property called DeleteRequest, which references the schema for the actual delete request. The DeleteRequest property is required and the wrapper is of type object.

This component defines a response wrapper for deleting paperless documents. It contains a single property called DeleteResponse, which references the DeleteResponse schema. The DeleteResponse property is required and the wrapper is of type object. The XML element is named DeleteResponse.

ShipperNumber.description: The Shipper's UPS Account Number.  Your UPS Account Number must have 'Upload Forms Created Offline' enabled to use this webservice.

DocumentID.description: DocumentId representing uploaded document to Forms History.  Only one DocumentID will be accepted for delete request.

DeleteRequest.description: Paperless Document API Request container for deleting user created forms.

flattened_text: The DeleteRequest object is used in the Paperless Document API to delete user-created forms. It contains properties for DocumentID (representing the uploaded document), Request, and ShipperNumber (the Shipper's UPS Account Number). The DocumentID must be a 26-character string, and the ShipperNumber must be a 6-character string with specific permissions enabled. The object is required to have Request, DocumentID, and ShipperNumber properties.

RequestOption.description: Enables the user to specify optional processing. Currently, there is no optional process in Paperless Document API.

DeleteRequest_Request.description: Contains Paperless Document API deleted request criteria components.

flattened_text: This component defines the criteria for a delete request in the Paperless Document API. It includes options for specifying processing, a subversion (not used), and a transaction reference. The component is limited to one instance and is represented as an object named "Request" in XML.

DeleteResponse.description: Paperless Document API response container for delete request.

flattened_text: This OpenAPI schema defines the response structure for deleting a document in the Paperless Document API. The response contains a single property called "Response," which references another schema. The "Response" property is required and the response is in XML format with the root element named "DeleteResponse."

Alert.description:
Alert Container.  There can be zero to many alert containers with code and description.

**NOTE:** For versions >= v2, this element will always be returned as an array. For requests using version = v1, this element will be returned as an array if there is more than one object and a single object if there is only 1.

flattened_text: This response contains information about a deletion operation. It includes an array of alert containers with codes and descriptions. The element 'Alert' may be returned as an array for versions >= v2 and as a single object for version = v1. Other properties include 'ResponseStatus' and 'TransactionReference'. The response is required to include 'ResponseStatus' and is represented as an object in XML with the name 'Response'.

Code.description: Identifies the success or failure of the transaction. Valid values are 0 = Failed and 1 = Successful.

Description.description: Describes Response Status Code.  Returns text of "Success" or "Failure".

flattened_text: This object represents the response status of a transaction. It includes two properties: "Code" indicates if the transaction was successful or failed, with values 0 for failed and 1 for successful; "Description" provides a text description of the status, either "Success" or "Failure". The object is required to have both properties and is represented in XML as "ResponseStatus".

Code.description: Warning code returned by the system.

Description.description: Warning messages returned by the system.

Response_Alert.description: Alert Container. There can be zero to many alert containers with code and description.

flattened_text: This defines an "Alert" object that can contain warning code and messages from the system. Each alert can have one code (up to 10 characters) and one description (up to 150 characters). Both code and description are required fields.

CustomerContext.description: The CustomerContext Information which will be echoed during response.

flattened_text: This defines a response object called "TransactionReference" that contains CustomerContext information. The CustomerContext field can be up to 512 characters long and will be included in the response.

This component, `PAPERLESSDOCUMENTRequestWrapper`, is an object that contains a single property called `PushToImageRepositoryRequest`. This property references the schema `PushToImageRepositoryRequest` and is required. The object is used to wrap requests related to pushing documents to an image repository.

This response wrapper contains a single property called PushToImageRepositoryResponse, which refers to another schema. The PushToImageRepositoryResponse property is required and the wrapper is of type object.

ShipperNumber.description: The Shipper's UPS Account Number.  Your UPS Account Number must have 'Upload Forms Created Offline' enabled to use this webservice.

FormsGroupID.description: FormsGroupID would be required in Push Request if user needs to update uploaded DocumentID(s) in Forms History.

ShipmentIdentifier.description: Shipment Identifier is required for this request.

ShipmentDateAndTime.description: The date and time of the processed shipment. Required only for small package shipments. The valid format is yyyy-MM-dd-HH.mm.ss

ShipmentType.description: Valid values are: 1 = small package, 2 = freight.

PRQConfirmationNumber.description: PRQ Confirmation being specified by client. Required for freight shipments.

TrackingNumber.description: UPS Tracking Number associated with this shipment. Required only for small package shipment.

PushToImageRepositoryRequest.description: Paperless Document API request container for push to Image Repository.

flattened_text: This API request container, "PushToImageRepositoryRequest," is used for pushing documents to an Image Repository. It includes various properties such as FormsGroupID, PRQConfirmationNumber, ShipmentDateAndTime, ShipmentIdentifier, ShipmentType, ShipperNumber, and TrackingNumber. Some properties are required, like ShipmentIdentifier, ShipmentType, Request, ShipperNumber, and FormsHistoryDocumentID. The request format must adhere to specific length and format requirements for each property.

RequestOption.description: Enables the user to specify optional processing. Currently, there is no optional process in Paperless Document API.

PushToImageRepositoryRequest_Request.description: Contains Paperless Document API PushToImageRepository request criteria components.

flattened_text: This object defines the criteria for a request to push documents to an image repository in the Paperless Document API. It includes options for specifying processing, a subversion field (not used), and a transaction reference. The object is limited to one instance and is represented in XML as "Request."

CustomerContext.description: The client uses CustomerContext to synchronize request/response pairs. The client establishes CustomerContext, which can contain any information you want; it is echoed back by the server.

Request_TransactionReference.description: TransactionReference identifies transactions between client and server.

flattened_text: This object, Request_TransactionReference, is used to identify transactions between a client and server. It includes a property called CustomerContext, which the client can use to synchronize request/response pairs. The CustomerContext can contain any desired information and is echoed back by the server. The maximum length of CustomerContext is 512 characters.

DocumentID.description: DocumentID represents a document uploaded to Forms History.

flattened_text: This object, PushToImageRepositoryRequest_FormsHistoryDocumentID, is a container for DocumentID(s) related to documents uploaded to Forms History. The DocumentID property is an array of strings with a maximum length of 26 characters and a maximum of 13 items. The DocumentID property is required in this object and is represented in XML as FormsHistoryDocumentID.

FormsGroupID.description: FormsGroupID is a consolidated ID representing one or multiple DocumentID(s).

PushToImageRepositoryResponse.description: Paperless Document API response container for Push To Image Repository request.

flattened_text: The `PushToImageRepositoryResponse` object is a container for the Paperless Document API response related to pushing documents to an image repository. It includes a `FormsGroupID` field, which is a unique ID representing one or more document IDs. The response body structure is defined in the `PushToImageRepositoryResponse_Response` schema. The `Response` field is required in the response object.

Alert.description:
Alert Container.  There can be zero to many alert containers with code and description.

**NOTE:** For versions >= v2, this element will always be returned as an array. For requests using version = v1, this element will be returned as an array if there is more than one object and a single object if there is only 1.

flattened_text: This response object contains information about alerts, response status, and transaction reference related to pushing to an image repository. Alerts can vary in number and include a code and description. The ResponseStatus field is mandatory, while TransactionReference provides additional details. The object is represented in XML as "Response."
This API endpoint allows users to upload a single paperless document. The request must include an UploadRequest object.
This component defines a wrapper for a single upload response in a paperless document system. The response structure is defined in the UploadResponse schema.

ShipperNumber.description: The Shipper's UPS Account Number.  Your UPS Account Number must have 'Upload Forms Created Offline' enabled to use this webservice.

UploadRequest.description: Paperless Document API Request container for uploading User Created Forms.

flattened_text: The UploadRequest object is used to upload user-created forms in the Paperless Document API. It includes the user's UPS Account Number and the forms to be uploaded. The UPS Account Number must have 'Upload Forms Created Offline' enabled. The object requires the Request, ShipperNumber, and UserCreatedForm properties. The ShipperNumber is a string with a length of 6 characters. The UserCreatedForm property is an array containing up to 13 items.

RequestOption.description: Enables the user to specify optional processing. Currently, there is no optional process in Paperless Document API.

UploadRequest_Request.description: Contains Paperless Document API upload request criteria components.

flattened_text: This component, UploadRequest_Request, is used to define criteria for uploading documents in the Paperless Document API. It includes RequestOption for optional processing (which is currently not available), SubVersion (not used), and TransactionReference.

UserCreatedFormFile.description:
The user created form file.  The maximum allowable size of each file is restricted to 10 MB. Should be a base64 encoded string.

Note: The maximum allowable size of each file is restriced to 1MB in CIE (Customer Integration Environment).

UserCreatedFormFileFormat.description: The UserCreatedForm file format.  The allowed file formats are bmp, doc, gif, jpg, pdf, png, rtf, tif, txt and xls. The only exceptions for having file format of length 4 character are docx and xlsx. All other file formats needs to be of length 3.

UserCreatedFormDocumentType.description: The type of documents in UserCreatedForm file.  The allowed document types are 001 - Authorization Form, 002 - Commercial Invoice, 003 - Certificate of Origin, 004 - Export Accompanying Document, 005 - Export License, 006 - Import Permit, 007 - One Time NAFTA, 008 - Other Document, 009 - Power of Attorney, 010 - Packing List, 011 - SED Document, 012 - Shipper's Letter of Instruction, 013 - Declaration. The total number of documents allowed per file or per shipment is 13. Each document type needs to be three digits.

UploadRequest_UserCreatedForm.description: The container for User Created Form. The container holds the file. Total number of allowed files per shipment is 13.

flattened_text: This API endpoint allows users to upload a User Created Form file. Each shipment can have up to 13 files. The User Created Form file must be in one of the specified document types, each represented by a three-digit code. The file size is limited to 10 MB and must be base64 encoded. The file format must be one of the specified types, with exceptions for docx and xlsx. The file name can be up to 300 characters long. The endpoint requires the User Created Form file, file name, file format, and document type.

UploadResponse.description: Paperless Document API Response Container for upload request.

flattened_text: The `UploadResponse` object is a container for the Paperless Document API upload request. It includes a `FormsHistoryDocumentID` and a `Response`. The `Response` property is required, and the object can only contain a maximum of one item. The object is represented in XML as `UploadResponse`.

Alert.description:
Alert Container.  There can be zero to many alert containers with code and description.

**NOTE:** For versions >= v2, this element will always be returned as an array. For requests using version = v1, this element will be returned as an array if there is more than one object and a single object if there is only 1.

flattened_text: The `UploadResponse_Response` object contains information about the response to an upload request. It includes an `Alert` container that may have multiple alerts with codes and descriptions. Note that for versions greater than or equal to v2, alerts will always be returned as an array. For `ResponseStatus`, `TransactionReference`, and `Alert`, specific schemas are referenced. The `ResponseStatus` property is required in the response.

DocumentID.description:
DocumentID represents a document uploaded to Forms History.

**NOTE:** For versions >= v2, this element will always be returned as an array. For requests using version = v1, this element will be returned as an array if there is more than one object and a single object if there is only 1.

flattened_text: This response contains the DocumentID for a document uploaded to Forms History. The DocumentID is returned as an array for versions >= v2 and as a single object for version = v1. The DocumentID is a string with a length of 26 characters.
This defines an "ErrorResponse" object that includes a reference to a common error response schema.

CommonErrorResponse.description: The error response containing any errors that occurred.

errors.description: The error array containing any errors that occurred.

flattened_text: This defines a common error response structure that includes an array of error messages. Each error message is defined in a separate schema called "ErrorMessage."

ErrorMessage.description: The error response containing any errors that occurred.

flattened_text: This defines an "ErrorMessage" object that includes an error code and message to convey any errors that occurred in the response.

info.title: PreNotification
info.description:
The Pre-Notification API allows customer applications to inform UPS operations of Dangerous Goods shipments as they are processed and will enter the UPS transportation network prior to an upload of manifest information at the end of the day. # Reference - Business Rules - Errors

Try out UPS APIs with example requests using Postman. Explore API documentation and sample applications through GitHub.

flattened_text: The Pre-Notification API allows customer applications to notify UPS about Dangerous Goods shipments before they enter the UPS transportation network. It enables users to check business rules and errors related to the API. You can test UPS APIs using Postman and access API documentation and sample applications on GitHub.
This OpenAPI specification defines two server URLs: one for the Customer Integration Environment at https://wwwcie.ups.com/api and one for Production at https://onlinetools.ups.com/api.
